# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oracle-database
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Indexes are schema objects that can speed access to table rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Index-organized tables are tables stored in an index structure.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An **index** is an optional structure, associated with a table or **table cluster**, that can sometimes speed data access.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Indexes are schema objects that are logically and physically independent of the data in the objects with which they are associated.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Thus, you can drop or create an index without physically affecting the indexed table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If you drop an index, then applications still work.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] However, access of previously indexed data can be slower.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For an analogy, suppose an HR manager has a shelf of cardboard boxes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Folders containing employee information are inserted randomly in the boxes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The folder for employee Whalen (ID 200) is 10 folders up from the bottom of box 1, whereas the folder for King (ID 100) is at the bottom of box 3.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] To locate a folder, the manager looks at every folder in box 1 from bottom to top, and then moves from box to box until the folder is found.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Similarly, the manager could create separate indexes for employee last names, department IDs, and so on.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The absence or presence of an index does not require a change in the wording of any SQL statement.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An index is a fast access path to a single row of data.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Given a data value that has been indexed, the index points directly to the location of the rows containing that value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] When an index exists on one or more columns of a table, the database can in some cases retrieve a small set of randomly distributed rows from the table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Indexes are one of many means of reducing disk I/O.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If a heap-organized table has no indexes, then the database must perform a full table scan to find a value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, a query of location `2700` in the unindexed `hr.departments` table requires the database to search every row in every block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] This approach does not scale well as data volumes increase.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Starting in Oracle Database 19c, Oracle Database can constantly monitor the application workload, creating and managing indexes automatically.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Automated indexing is implemented as a database task that runs at a fixed interval.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Indexes are usable (default) or unusable, visible (default) or invisible.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A **key** is a set of columns or expressions on which you can build an index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Although the terms are often used interchangeably, indexes and keys are different.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Indexes are structures stored in the database that users manage using SQL statements.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In the preceding statement, the `customer_id` column is the index key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The index itself is named `ord_customer_ix`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Primary and unique keys automatically have indexes, but you might want to create an index on a foreign key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A **composite index**, also called a **concatenated index**, is an index on multiple columns in a table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Place columns in a composite index in the order that makes the most sense for the queries that will retrieve data.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The columns need not be adjacent in the table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Composite indexes can speed retrieval of data for `SELECT` statements in which the `WHERE` clause references all or the leading portion of the columns in the composite index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Therefore, the order of the columns used in the definition is important.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In general, the most commonly accessed columns go first.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, suppose an application frequently queries the `last_name`, `job_id`, and `salary` columns in the `employees` table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Also assume that `last_name` has high cardinality, which means that the number of distinct values is large compared to the number of table rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Queries that access all three columns, only the `last_name` column, or only the `last_name` and `job_id` columns use this index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In this example, queries that do not access the `last_name` column do not use the index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In some cases, such as when the leading column has very low cardinality, the database may use a skip scan of this index (see "Index Skip Scan").
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, a nonpartitioned index, global partitioned index, and locally partitioned index can exist for the same table columns in the same order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Only one index with the same number of columns in the same order can be visible at any one time.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] This capability enables you to migrate applications without the need to drop an existing index and re-create it with different attributes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Also, this capability is useful in an OLTP database when an index key keeps increasing, causing the database to insert new entries into the same set of index blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] To alleviate such "hot spots," you could evolve the index from a nonpartitioned index into a global partitioned index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If indexes on the same set of columns do not differ in type or partitioning scheme, then these indexes must use different column permutations.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Unique indexes guarantee that no two rows of a table have duplicate values in the key column or columns.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, your application may require that no two employees have the same employee ID.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In a unique index, one rowid exists for each data value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The data in the leaf blocks is sorted only by key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Nonunique indexes permit duplicates values in the indexed column or columns.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, the `first_name` column of the `employees` table may contain multiple `Mike` values.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For a nonunique index, the rowid is included in the key in sorted order, so nonunique indexes are sorted by the index key and rowid (ascending).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Oracle Database does not index table rows in which all key columns are null, except for bitmap indexes or when the cluster key column value is null.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Oracle Database provides several indexing schemes, which provide complementary performance functionality.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] B-tree indexes are the standard index type.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] They are excellent for highly selective indexes (few rows correspond to each index entry) and primary key indexes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Used as concatenated indexes, a B-tree index can retrieve data sorted by the indexed columns.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] B-tree indexes have the subtypes shown in the following table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The following table shows types of indexes that do not use a B-tree structure.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database automatically maintains and uses indexes after they are created.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Indexes automatically reflect data changes to their underlying tables.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Examples of changes include adding, updating, and deleting rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Retrieval performance of indexed data remains almost constant, even as rows are inserted.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] However, the presence of many indexes on a table degrades DML performance because the database must also update the indexes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Oracle Database stores index data in an index segment.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Space available for index data in a data block is the data block size minus block overhead, entry overhead, rowid, and one length byte for each value indexed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The tablespace of an index segment is either the default tablespace of the owner or a tablespace specifically named in the `CREATE INDEX` statement.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For ease of administration you can store an index in a separate tablespace from its table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, you may choose not to back up tablespaces containing only indexes, which can be rebuilt, and so decrease the time and storage required for backups.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] B-trees, short for balanced trees, are the most common type of database index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A B-tree index is an ordered list of values divided into ranges.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] By associating a key with a row or range of rows, B-trees provide excellent retrieval performance for a wide range of queries, including exact match and range searches.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The following figure illustrates the structure of a B-tree index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The example shows an index on the `department_id` column, which is a foreign key column in the `employees` table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A B-tree index has two types of blocks: the branch block for searching, and the leaf block for storing key values.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The upper-level branch blocks of a B-tree index contain index data that points to lower-level index blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In Figure 3-1, the root branch block has an entry `0-40`, which points to the leftmost block in the next branch level.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] This branch block contains entries such as `0-10` and `11-19`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Each of these entries points to a leaf block that contains key values that fall in the range.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A B-tree index is balanced because all leaf blocks automatically stay at the same depth.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Thus, retrieval of any record from anywhere in the index takes approximately the same amount of time.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The height of the index is the number of blocks required to go from the root block to a leaf block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In Figure 3-1, the index has a height of 3 and a branch level of 2.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Branch blocks store the minimum key prefix needed to make a branching decision between two keys.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] This technique enables the database to fit as much data as possible on each branch block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The branch blocks contain a pointer to the child block containing the key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The number of keys and pointers is limited by the block size.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The leaf blocks contain every indexed data value and a corresponding rowid used to locate the actual row.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Within a leaf block, a key and rowid is linked to its left and right sibling entries.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The leaf blocks themselves are also doubly linked.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In Figure 3-1 the leftmost leaf block (`0-10`) is linked to the second leaf block (`11-19`).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Indexes in columns with character data are based on the binary values of the characters in the database character set.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In an **index scan**, the database retrieves a row by traversing the index, using the indexed column values specified by the statement.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If the database scans the index for a value, then it will find this value in n I/Os where n is the height of the B-tree index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] This is the basic principle behind Oracle Database indexes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If a SQL statement accesses only indexed columns, then the database reads values directly from the index rather than from the table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If the statement accesses nonindexed columns in addition to the indexed columns, then the database uses rowids to find the rows in the table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Typically, the database retrieves table data by alternately reading an index block and then a table block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In a full index scan, the database reads the entire index in order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A full index scan is available if a predicate (`WHERE` clause) in the SQL statement references a column in the index, and in some circumstances when no predicate is specified.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A full scan can eliminate sorting because the data is ordered by index key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In this example, the `department_id`, `last_name`, and `salary` are a composite key in an index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Oracle Database performs a full scan of the index, reading it in sorted order (ordered by department ID and last name) and filtering on the salary attribute.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In this way, the database scans a set of data smaller than the `employees` table, which contains more columns than are included in the query, and avoids sorting the data.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A fast full index scan is a full index scan in which the database accesses the data in the index itself without accessing the table, and the database reads the index blocks in no particular order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The `last_name` column has a not null constraint.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An index range scan is an ordered scan of an index in which one or more leading columns of an index are specified in conditions, and 0, 1, or more values are possible for an index key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A condition specifies a combination of one or more expressions and logical (Boolean) operators.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] It returns a value of `TRUE`, `FALSE`, or `UNKNOWN`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database commonly uses an index range scan to access selective data.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The selectivity is the percentage of rows in the table that the query selects, with 0 meaning no rows and 1 meaning all rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Selectivity is tied to a query predicate, such as `WHERE last_name LIKE 'A%'`, or a combination of predicates.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A predicate becomes more selective as the value approaches 0 and less selective (or more unselective) as the value approaches 1.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, a user queries employees whose last names begin with `A`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database could use a range scan because the `last_name` column is specified in the predicate and multiples rowids are possible for each index key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, two employees are named Austin, so two rowids are associated with the key `Austin`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An index range scan can be bounded on both sides, as in a query for departments with IDs between 10 and 40, or bounded on only one side, as in a query for IDs over 40.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] To scan the index, the database moves backward or forward through the leaf blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, a scan for IDs between 10 and 40 locates the first index leaf block that contains the lowest key value that is 10 or greater.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The scan then proceeds horizontally through the linked list of leaf nodes until it locates a value greater than 40.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In contrast to an index range scan, an index unique scan must have either 0 or 1 rowid associated with an index key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database performs a unique scan when a predicate references all of the columns in the key of a `UNIQUE` index using an equality operator.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An index unique scan stops processing as soon as it finds the first record because no second record is possible.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In this case, the database can use an index unique scan to locate the rowid for the employee whose ID is 5.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An **index skip scan** uses logical subindexes of a composite index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database "skips" through a single index as if it were searching separate indexes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Skip scanning is beneficial if there are few distinct values in the leading column of a composite index and many distinct values in the nonleading key of the index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database may choose an index skip scan when the leading column of the composite index is not specified in a query predicate.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The `customers` table has a column `cust_gender` whose values are either `M` or `F`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Assume that a composite index exists on the columns (`cust_gender`, `cust_email`).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database can use a skip scan of this index even though `cust_gender` is not specified in the `WHERE` clause.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In a skip scan, the number of logical subindexes is determined by the number of distinct values in the leading column.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In the preceding example, the leading column has two possible values.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database logically splits the index into one subindex with the key `F` and a second subindex with the key `M`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] When searching for the record for the customer whose email is `Abbey@company.example.com`, the database searches the subindex with the value `F` first and then searches the subindex with the value `M`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The **index clustering factor** measures row order in relation to an indexed value such as employee last name.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] As the degree of order increases, the clustering factor decreases.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Assume that the `employees` table fits into two data blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Table 3-3 depicts the rows in the two data blocks (the ellipses indicate data that is not shown).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Rows are stored in the blocks in order of last name (shown in bold).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, the bottom row in data block 1 describes Abel, the next row up describes Ande, and so on alphabetically until the top row in block 1 for Steven King.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The bottom row in block 2 describes Kochar, the next row up describes Kumar, and so on alphabetically until the last row in the block for Zlotkey.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Assume that an index exists on the last name column.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Assume that a separate index exists on the employee ID column.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The clustering factor for `EMP_NAME_IX` is low, which means that adjacent index entries in a single leaf block tend to point to rows in the same data blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The clustering factor for `EMP_EMP_ID_PK` is high, which means that adjacent index entries in the same leaf block are much less likely to point to rows in the same data blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] A **reverse key index** is a type of B-tree index that physically reverses the bytes of each index key while keeping the column order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, if the index key is `20`, and if the two bytes stored for this key in hexadecimal are `C1,15` in a standard B-tree index, then a reverse key index stores the bytes as `15,C1`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Reversing the key solves the problem of contention for leaf blocks in the right side of a B-tree index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] This problem can be especially acute in an Oracle Real Application Clusters (Oracle RAC) database in which multiple instances repeatedly modify the same block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, in an `orders` table the primary keys for orders are sequential.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] One instance in the cluster adds order 20, while another adds 21, with each instance writing its key to the same leaf block on the right-hand side of the index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In a reverse key index, the reversal of the byte order distributes inserts across all leaf keys in the index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, keys such as 20 and 21 that would have been adjacent in a standard key index are now stored far apart in separate blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Thus, I/O for insertions of sequential keys is more evenly distributed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Because the data in the index is not sorted by column key when it is stored, the reverse key arrangement eliminates the ability to run an index range scanning query in some cases.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, if a user issues a query for order IDs greater than 20, then the database cannot start with the block containing this ID and proceed horizontally through the leaf blocks.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In an **ascending index**, Oracle Database stores data in ascending order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] By default, character data is ordered by the binary values contained in each byte of the value, numeric data from smallest to largest number, and date from earliest to latest value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Oracle Database sorts the `hr.employees` table on the `department_id` column.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] It loads the ascending index with the `department_id` and corresponding rowid values in ascending order, starting with `0`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] When it uses the index, Oracle Database searches the sorted `department_id` values and uses the associated rowids to locate rows having the requested `department_id` value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] By specifying the `DESC` keyword in the `CREATE INDEX` statement, you can create a descending index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In this case, the index stores data on a specified column or columns in descending order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If the index in Table 3-3 on the `employees.department_id` column were descending, then the leaf blocking containing `250` would be on the left side of the tree and block with `0` on the right.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The default search through a descending index is from highest to lowest value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Descending indexes are useful when a query sorts some columns ascending and others descending.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If a user queries `hr.employees` for last names in ascending order (A to Z) and department IDs in descending order (high to low), then the database can use this index to retrieve the data and avoid the extra step of sorting it.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] To reduce space in indexes, Oracle Database can employ different compression algorithms.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Oracle Database can use prefix compression, also known as key compression, to compress portions of the primary key column values in a B-tree index or an index-organized table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Prefix compression can greatly reduce the space consumed by the index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An uncompressed index entry has one piece.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] An index entry using prefix compression has two pieces: a prefix entry, which is the grouping piece, and a suffix entry, which is the unique or nearly unique piece.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The database achieves compression by sharing the prefix entries among the suffix entries in an index block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If a key is not defined to have a unique piece, then the database provides one by appending a rowid to the grouping piece.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] By default, the prefix of a unique index consists of all key columns excluding the last one, whereas the prefix of a nonunique index consists of all key columns.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In the preceding example, an index key might be `online,0`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The rowid is stored in the key data portion of the entry, and is not part of the key itself.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If you create a unique index on a single column, then Oracle Database cannot use prefix key compression because no common prefixes exist.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Also assume that repeated values occur in the `order_mode` and `order_status` columns.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In the preceding example, the key prefix would consist of a concatenation of the `order_mode` and `order_status` values, as in `online,0`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The suffix consists in the rowid, as in `AAAPvCAAFAAAAFaAAa`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The rowid makes the whole index entry unique because a rowid is itself unique in the database.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] If the index in the preceding example were created with default prefix compression (specified by the `COMPRESS` keyword), then duplicate key prefixes such as `online`,`0` and `online`,`3` would be compressed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Suffix entries (the rowids) form the compressed version of index rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Each suffix entry references a prefix entry, which is stored in the same index block as the suffix.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Alternatively, you could specify a prefix length when creating an index that uses prefix compression.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] For example, if you specified `COMPRESS 1`, then the prefix would be `order_mode` and the suffix would be `order_status,rowid`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] The index stores a specific prefix once per leaf block at most.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Only keys in the leaf blocks of a B-tree index are compressed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In the branch blocks the key suffix can be truncated, but the key is not compressed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Starting with Oracle Database 12c Release 1 (12.1.0.2), **advanced index compression** improves on traditional prefix compression for supported indexes on heap-organized tables.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Prefix compression has limitations for types of indexes supported, compression ratio, and ease of use.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Unlike prefix compression, which uses fixed duplicate key elimination for every block, advanced index compression uses adaptive duplicate key elimination on a per-block basis.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Advanced index compression works at the block level to provide the best compression for each block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] In releases previous to Oracle Database 12c Release 2 (12.2), the only form of advanced index compression was low compression (`COMPRESS ADVANCED LOW`).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] Now you can also specify high compression (`COMPRESS ADVANCED HIGH`), which is the default.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] When you apply `HIGH` compression, all blocks have compression.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] When you apply `LOW` compression, the database may leave some blocks uncompressed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p01] You can use statistics to determine how many blocks were left uncompressed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In a **bitmap index**, the database stores a bitmap for each index key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In a conventional B-tree index, one index entry points to a single row.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In a bitmap index, each index key stores pointers to multiple rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Bitmap indexes are primarily designed for data warehousing or environments in which queries reference many columns in an ad hoc fashion.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For a data warehouse example, the `sh.customers` table has a `cust_gender` column with only two possible values: `M` and `F`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Suppose that queries for the number of customers of a particular gender are common.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In this case, the `customers.cust_gender` column would be a candidate for a bitmap index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Each bit in the bitmap corresponds to a possible rowid.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] If the bit is set, then the row with the corresponding rowid contains the key value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A mapping function converts the bit position to an actual rowid, so the bitmap index provides the same functionality as a B-tree index although it uses a different internal representation.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] If the indexed column in a single row is updated, then the database locks the index key entry (for example, `M` or `F`) and not the individual bit mapped to the updated row.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Because a key points to many rows, DML on indexed data typically locks all of these rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For this reason, bitmap indexes are not appropriate for many OLTP applications.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In this example, some columns of `sh.customers` table are candidates for a bitmap index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The `cust_marital_status` and `cust_gender` columns have low cardinality, whereas `cust_id` and `cust_last_name` do not.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Thus, bitmap indexes may be appropriate on `cust_marital_status` and `cust_gender`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A bitmap index is probably not useful for the other columns.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Instead, a unique B-tree index on these columns would likely provide the most efficient representation and retrieval.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Table 3-4 illustrates the bitmap index for the `cust_gender` column output shown in the preceding example.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] It consists of two separate bitmaps, one for each gender.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A mapping function converts each bit in the bitmap to a rowid of the `customers` table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Each bit value depends on the values of the corresponding row in the table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, the bitmap for the `M` value contains a `1` as its first bit because the gender is `M` in the first row of the `customers` table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The bitmap `cust_gender='M'` has a `0` for the bits in rows 2, 6, and 7 because these rows do not contain `M` as their value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Bitmap indexes can include keys that consist entirely of null values, unlike B-tree indexes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Indexing nulls can be useful for some SQL statements, such as queries with the aggregate function `COUNT`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Bitmap indexes can process this query efficiently by counting the number of `1` values in the resulting bitmap, as illustrated in Table 3-5.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] To identify the customers who satisfy the criteria, Oracle Database can use the resulting bitmap to access the table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Bitmap indexing efficiently merges indexes that correspond to several conditions in a `WHERE` clause.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Rows that satisfy some, but not all, conditions are filtered out before the table itself is accessed.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] This technique improves response time, often dramatically.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A **bitmap join index** is a bitmap index for the **join** of two or more tables.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For each value in a table column, the index stores the rowid of the corresponding row in the indexed table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In contrast, a standard bitmap index is created on a single table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A bitmap join index is an efficient means of reducing the volume of data that must be joined by performing restrictions in advance.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For an example of when a bitmap join index would be useful, assume that users often query the number of employees with a particular job type.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The preceding query would typically use an index on `jobs.job_title` to retrieve the rows for `Accountant` and then the job ID, and an index on `employees.job_id` to find the matching rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] As illustrated in the following figure, the index key is `jobs.job_title` and the indexed table is `employees`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Conceptually, `employees_bm_idx` is an index of the `jobs.title` column in the SQL query shown in the following query (sample output included).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The `job_title` key in the index points to rows in the `employees` table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A query of the number of accountants can use the index to avoid accessing the `employees` and `jobs` tables because the index itself contains the requested information.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In a data warehouse, the join condition is an equijoin (it uses the equality operator) between the primary key columns of the dimension tables and the foreign key columns in the fact table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Bitmap join indexes are sometimes much more efficient in storage than materialized join views, an alternative for materializing joins in advance.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Oracle Database uses a B-tree index structure to store bitmaps for each indexed key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, if `jobs.job_title` is the key column of a bitmap index, then one B-tree stores the index data.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The leaf blocks store the individual bitmaps.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Assume that the `jobs.job_title` column has unique values `Shipping Clerk`, `Stock Clerk`, and several others.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The same job title appears in multiple entries because the rowid range differs.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A session updates the job ID of one employee from `Shipping Clerk` to `Stock Clerk`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In this case, the session requires exclusive access to the index key entry for the old value (`Shipping Clerk`) and the new value (`Stock Clerk`).
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Oracle Database locks the rows pointed to by these two entries—but not the rows pointed to by `Accountant` or any other key—until the `UPDATE` commits.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The data for a bitmap index is stored in one segment.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Oracle Database stores each bitmap in one or more pieces.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Each piece occupies part of a single data block.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A function-based index computes the value of a function or expression involving one or more columns and stores it in an index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A function-based index can be either a B-tree or a bitmap index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The indexed function can be an arithmetic expression or an expression that contains a SQL function, user-defined PL/SQL function, package function, or C callout.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, a function could add the values in two columns.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Function-based indexes are efficient for evaluating statements that contain functions in their `WHERE` clauses.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The database only uses the function-based index when the function is included in a query.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] When the database processes `INSERT` and `UPDATE` statements, however, it must still evaluate the function to process the statement.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Function-based indexes defined on the SQL functions `UPPER(``column_name``)` or `LOWER(``column_name``)` facilitate case-insensitive searches.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, suppose that the `first_name` column in `employees` contains mixed-case characters.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A function-based index is also useful for indexing only specific rows in a table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, the `cust_valid` column in the `sh.customers` table has either `I` or `A` as a value.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] To index only the `A` rows, you could write a function that returns a null value for any rows other than the `A` rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For queries with expressions in a `WHERE` clause, the optimizer might use an index range scan on a function-based index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The range scan access path is especially beneficial when the predicate is highly selective, that is, when it chooses relatively few rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In Example 3-7, if an index is built on the expression `12*salary*commission_pct`, then the optimizer can use an index range scan.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A virtual column is also useful for speeding access to data derived from expressions.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, you could define virtual column `annual_sal` as `12*salary*commission_pct` and create a function-based index on `annual_sal`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The optimizer performs expression matching by parsing the expression in a SQL statement and then comparing the expression trees of the statement and the function-based index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] This comparison is case-insensitive and ignores blank spaces.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Different queries may use different types of index scans.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] An application domain index is a customized index specific to an application.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] You can encapsulate application-specific index management routines as an indextype schema object, and then define a domain index on table columns or attributes of an object type.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Extensible indexing can efficiently process application-specific operators.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The application software, called the cartridge, controls the structure and content of a domain index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The database interacts with the application to build, maintain, and search the domain index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The index structure itself can be stored in the database as an index-organized table or externally as a file.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] An index-organized table is a table stored in a variation of a B-tree index structure.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In contrast, a heap-organized table inserts rows where they fit.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In an index-organized table, rows are stored in an index defined on the primary key for the table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Each index entry in the B-tree also stores the non-key column values.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Thus, the index is the data, and the data is the index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Applications manipulate index-organized tables just like heap-organized tables, using SQL statements.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For an analogy of an index-organized table, suppose a human resources manager has a book case of cardboard boxes.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Each box is labeled with a number—1, 2, 3, 4, and so on—but the boxes do not sit on the shelves in sequential order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Instead, each box contains a pointer to the shelf location of the next box in the sequence.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Folders containing employee records are stored in each box.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Employee King has ID 100, which is the lowest ID, so his folder is at the bottom of box 1.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The folder for employee 101 is on top of 100, 102 is on top of 101, and so on until box 1 is full.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The next folder in the sequence is at the bottom of box 2.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In this analogy, ordering folders by employee ID makes it possible to search efficiently for folders without having to maintain a separate index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Suppose a user requests the records for employees 107, 120, and 122.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Instead of searching an index in one step and retrieving the folders in a separate step, the manager can search the folders in sequential order and retrieve each folder as found.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Index-organized tables provide faster access to table rows by primary key or a valid prefix of the key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The presence of non-key columns of a row in the leaf block avoids an additional data block I/O.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, the salary of employee 100 is stored in the index row itself.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Also, because rows are stored in primary key order, range access by the primary key or prefix involves minimal block I/Os.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Another benefit is the avoidance of the space overhead of a separate primary key index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Index-organized tables are useful when related pieces of data must be stored together or data must be physically stored in a specific order.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A typical use of this type of table is for information retrieval, spatial data, and OLAP applications.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The database system performs all operations on index-organized tables by manipulating the B-tree index structure.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The following table summarizes the differences between index-organized tables and heap-organized tables.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Figure 3-3 illustrates the structure of an index-organized `departments` table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The leaf blocks contain the rows of the table, ordered sequentially by primary key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, the first value in the first leaf block shows a department ID of `20`, department name of `Marketing`, manager ID of `201`, and location ID of `1800`.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] An index-organized table stores all data in the same structure and does not need to store the rowid.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Thus, the number of block I/Os in this example is double the number in the index-organized example.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] When creating an index-organized table, you can specify a separate segment as a row overflow area.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In index-organized tables, B-tree index entries can be large because they contain an entire row, so a separate segment to contain the entries is useful.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In contrast, B-tree entries are usually small because they consist of the key and rowid.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A **secondary index** is an index on an index-organized table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] In a sense, a secondary index is an index on an index.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] It is an independent schema object and is stored separately from the index-organized table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Oracle Database uses row identifiers called logical rowids for index-organized tables.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A logical rowid is a base64-encoded representation of the table primary key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The logical rowid length depends on the primary key length.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Rows in index leaf blocks can move within or between blocks because of insertions.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Rows in index-organized tables do not migrate as heap-organized rows do.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Because rows in index-organized tables do not have permanent physical addresses, the database uses logical rowids based on primary key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, assume that the `departments` table is index-organized.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The `location_id` column stores the ID of each department.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Secondary indexes provide fast and efficient access to index-organized tables using columns that are neither the primary key nor a prefix of the primary key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For example, a query of the names of departments whose ID is greater than 1700 could use the secondary index to speed data access.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Secondary indexes use logical rowids to locate table rows.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A logical rowid includes a **physical guess**, which is the physical rowid of the index entry when it was first made.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Oracle Database can use physical guesses to probe directly into the leaf block of the index-organized table, bypassing the primary key search.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] When the physical location of a row changes, the logical rowid remains valid even if it contains a physical guess that is stale.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] For a heap-organized table, access by a secondary index involves a scan of the secondary index and an additional I/O to fetch the data block containing the row.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A secondary index on an index-organized table can be a **bitmap index**.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] A bitmap index stores a bitmap for each index key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] When bitmap indexes exist on an index-organized table, all the bitmap indexes use a heap-organized mapping table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The mapping table stores the logical rowids of the index-organized table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Each mapping table row stores one logical rowid for the corresponding index-organized table row.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The database accesses a bitmap index using a search key.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] If the database finds the key, then the bitmap entry is converted to a physical rowid.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] With heap-organized tables, the database uses the physical rowid to access the base table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] With index-organized tables, the database uses the physical rowid to access the mapping table, which in turn yields a logical rowid that the database uses to access the index-organized table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] The following figure illustrates index access for a query of the `departments_iot` table.
[src:oracle-database/indexes-and-index-organized-tables-p02] Movement of rows in an index-organized table does not leave the bitmap indexes built on that index-organized table unusable.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] This chapter provides an overview of Oracle Database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Every organization has information that it must store and manage to meet its requirements.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, a corporation must collect and maintain human resources records for its employees.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] This information must be available to those who need it.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An information system is a formal system for storing and processing information.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An information system could be a set of cardboard boxes containing manila folders along with rules for how to store and retrieve the folders.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] However, most companies today use a database to automate their information systems.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database is an organized collection of information treated as a unit.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The purpose of a database is to collect, store, and retrieve related information for use by database applications.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database management system (DBMS) is software that controls the storage, organization, and retrieval of data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database application is a software program that interacts with a database to access and manipulate data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The preceding database management systems stored data in rigid, predetermined relationships.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Because no data definition language existed, changing the structure of the data was difficult.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Also, these systems lacked a simple query language, which hindered application development.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In his seminal 1970 paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks," E.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Codd defined a relational model based on mathematical set theory.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Today, the most widely accepted database model is the relational model.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A relational database is a database that conforms to the relational model.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A relational database stores data in a set of simple relations.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A tuple is an unordered set of attribute values.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A table is a two-dimensional representation of a relation in the form of rows (tuples) and columns (attributes).
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Each row in a table has the same set of columns.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A relational database is a database that stores data in relations (tables).
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, a relational database could store information about company employees in an employee table, a department table, and a salary table.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The relational model is the basis for a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An RDBMS moves data into a database, stores the data, and retrieves it so that applications can manipulate it.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An RDBMS that implements object-oriented features such as user-defined types, inheritance, and polymorphism is called an object-relational database management system (ORDBMS).
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database has extended the relational model to an object-relational model, making it possible to store complex business models in a relational database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The current version of Oracle Database is the result of over 35 years of innovative development.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] One characteristic of an RDBMS is the independence of physical data storage from logical data structures.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In Oracle Database, a database schema is a collection of logical data structures, or schema objects.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database user owns a database schema, which has the same name as the user name.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Schema objects are user-created structures that directly refer to the data in the database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The database supports many types of schema objects, the most important of which are tables and indexes.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A schema object is one type of database object.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Some database objects, such as profiles and roles, do not reside in schemas.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A table describes an entity such as employees.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] You define a table with a table name, such as `employees`, and set of columns.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In general, you give each column a name, a data type, and a width when you create the table.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A column identifies an attribute of the entity described by the table, whereas a row identifies an instance of the entity.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, attributes of the employees entity correspond to columns for employee ID and last name.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] You can optionally specify a rule, called an integrity constraint, for a column.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] One example is a `NOT NULL` integrity constraint.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] This constraint forces the column to contain a value in every row.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An **index** is an optional data structure that you can create on one or more columns of a table.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Indexes can increase the performance of data retrieval.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] When processing a request, the database can use available indexes to locate the requested rows efficiently.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Indexes are useful when applications often query a specific row or range of rows.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Indexes are logically and physically independent of the data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Thus, you can drop and create indexes with no effect on the tables or other indexes.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] All applications continue to function after you drop an index.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A general requirement for a DBMS is to adhere to accepted industry standards for a data access language.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] SQL is a set-based declarative language that provides an interface to an RDBMS such as Oracle Database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Procedural languages such as C describe how things should be done.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] SQL is nonprocedural and describes what should be done.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] SQL is the ANSI standard language for relational databases.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] All operations on the data in an Oracle database are performed using SQL statements.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, you use SQL to create tables and query and modify data in tables.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A SQL statement can be thought of as a very simple, but powerful, computer program or instruction.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Users specify the result that they want (for example, the names of employees), not how to derive it.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] SQL unifies the preceding tasks in one consistent language.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle SQL is an implementation of the ANSI standard.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle SQL supports numerous features that extend beyond standard SQL.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] PL/SQL is integrated with Oracle Database, enabling you to use all of the Oracle Database SQL statements, functions, and data types.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] You can use PL/SQL to control the flow of a SQL program, use variables, and write error-handling procedures.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A primary benefit of PL/SQL is the ability to store application logic in the database itself.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A PL/SQL procedure or function is a schema object that consists of a set of SQL statements and other PL/SQL constructs, grouped together, stored in the database, and run as a unit to solve a specific problem or to perform a set of related tasks.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The principal benefit of server-side programming is that built-in functionality can be deployed anywhere.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database can also store program units written in Java.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A Java stored procedure is a Java method published to SQL and stored in the database for general use.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] You can call existing PL/SQL programs from Java and Java programs from PL/SQL.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database is designed as a multiuser database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The database must ensure that multiple users can work concurrently without corrupting one another's data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A **transaction** is a logical, atomic unit of work that contains one or more SQL statements.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An RDBMS must be able to group SQL statements so that they are either all committed, which means they are applied to the database, or all rolled back, which means they are undone.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An illustration of the need for transactions is a funds transfer from a savings account to a checking account.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Record the transaction in the transaction journal.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database guarantees that all three operations succeed or fail as a unit.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, if a hardware failure prevents a statement in the transaction from executing, then the other statements must be rolled back.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Transactions are one feature that set Oracle Database apart from a file system.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] If you perform an atomic operation that updates several files, and if the system fails halfway through, then the files will not be consistent.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In contrast, a transaction moves an Oracle database from one consistent state to another.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The basic principle of a transaction is "all or nothing": an atomic operation succeeds or fails as a whole.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A requirement of a multiuser RDBMS is the control of **data concurrency**, which is the simultaneous access of the same data by multiple users.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Without concurrency controls, users could change data improperly, compromising data integrity.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, one user could update a row while a different user simultaneously updates it.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] If multiple users access the same data, then one way of managing concurrency is to make users wait.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] However, the goal of a DBMS is to reduce wait time so it is either nonexistent or negligible.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] All SQL statements that modify data must proceed with as little interference as possible.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Destructive interactions, which are interactions that incorrectly update data or alter underlying data structures, must be avoided.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database uses locks to control concurrent access to data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A lock is a mechanism that prevents destructive interaction between transactions accessing a shared resource.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Locks help ensure data integrity while allowing maximum concurrent access to data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In Oracle Database, each user must see a consistent view of the data, including visible changes made by a user's own transactions and committed transactions of other users.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, the database must prevent the dirty read problem, which occurs when one transaction sees uncommitted changes made by another concurrent transaction.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database always enforces statement-level read consistency, which guarantees that the data that a single query returns is committed and consistent for a single point in time.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Depending on the transaction isolation level, this point is the time at which the statement was opened or the time the transaction began.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The Oracle Flashback Query feature enables you to specify this point in time explicitly.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The database can also provide read consistency to all queries in a transaction, known as transaction-level read consistency.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In this case, each statement in a transaction sees data from the same point in time, which is the time at which the transaction began.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database server is the key to information management.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In general, a server reliably manages a large amount of data in a multiuser environment so that users can concurrently access the same data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database server also prevents unauthorized access and provides efficient solutions for failure recovery.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An Oracle database server consists of a database and at least one **database instance**, commonly referred to as simply an **instance**.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Because an instance and a database are so closely connected, the term **Oracle database** is sometimes used to refer to both instance and database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The following figure shows a database and its instance.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For each user connection to the instance, a client process runs the application.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Each client process is associated with its own server process.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The server process has its own private session memory, known as the program global area (PGA).
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Although in the strict sense an Oracle database is a set of physical structures (files and memory structures), applications can interact with multiple logical databases inside a single physical database, or a single logical database distributed across multiple physical databases.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] enables an Oracle database to be a multitenant container database (CDB).
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A non-CDB is a traditional Oracle database that cannot contain PDBs.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A CDB is a single physical database that contains zero, one, or many user-created pluggable databases.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A pluggable database (PDB) is a portable collection of schemas, schema objects, and nonschema objects that appears to an Oracle Net client as a non-CDB.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] CDBs and non-CDBs have architectural differences.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] This manual assumes the architecture of a non-CDB unless otherwise indicated.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The multitenant architecture solves a number of problems posed by the traditional non-CDB architecture.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Large enterprises may use hundreds or thousands of databases, often running on different platforms on multiple physical servers.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Modern servers are able to handle heavier workloads than before.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database may use only a fraction of the server hardware capacity.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] This approach wastes both hardware and human resources.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Starting in Oracle Database 12c, you must create a database as either a CDB or non-CDB.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] You can plug a traditional non-CDB into a CDB as a PDB.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The PDB/non-CDB compatibility guarantee means that a PDB behaves the same as a non-CDB as seen from a client connecting with Oracle Net.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The following figure shows two separate non-CDBs: `hr` and `sales`.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Each non-CDB has its own memory and set of database files, and resides on its own computer.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Each non-CDB has its own dedicated user application.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The following figure shows the same data after being consolidated into the CDB named `MYCDB`.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Physically, `MYCDB` is an Oracle database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] `MYCDB` has one database instance, although multiple instances are possible in Oracle Real Application Clusters, and one set of database files, just like a non-CDB.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] `MYCDB` contains two PDBs: `hrpdb` and `salespdb`.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] As shown in Figure 1-3, these PDBs appear to their respective applications just as they did before database consolidation.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] To administer the CDB itself or any PDB within it, a CDB administrator can connect to the CDB root, which is a collection of schemas, schema objects, and nonschema objects to which all PDBs belong.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Starting in Oracle Database 12c Release 2 (12.2), an application container is an optional, user-created container that stores data and metadata for one or more application models.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An application (also called an application model) is a named, versioned set of common data and metadata stored in the application root.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, the application model might include definitions of tables, views, user accounts, and PL/SQL packages that are common to a set of PDBs.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In some ways, an application container functions as an application-specific CDB within a CDB.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An application container, like the CDB itself, can include multiple application PDBs, and enables these PDBs to share metadata and data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, a SaaS deployment can use multiple application PDBs, each for a separate customer, which share application metadata and data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, in the following figure, `sales_app` is the application model in the application root.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The application PDB named `cust1_pdb` contains sales data only for customer 1, whereas the application PDB named `cust2_pdb` contains sales data only for customer 2.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Plugging, unplugging, cloning, and other PDB-level operations are available for individual customer PDBs.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Sharding is a database scaling technique based on horizontal partitioning of data across multiple Oracle databases.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Applications perceive the pool of databases as a single logical database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Key benefits of sharding for OLTP applications include linear scalability, fault containment, and geographical data distribution.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Sharding is well suited to deployment in the Oracle Cloud.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Unlike NoSQL data stores that implement sharding, Oracle Sharding provides the benefits of sharding without sacrificing the capabilities of an enterprise RDBMS.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In a sharding architecture, each database is hosted on a dedicated server with its own local resources - CPU, memory, flash, or disk.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Each database in such configuration is called a **shard**.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] All of the shards together make up a single logical database, which is referred to as a **sharded database**.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Horizontal partitioning involves splitting a database table across shards so that each shard contains the table with the same columns but a different subset of rows.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A table split up in this manner is also known as a **sharded table**.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The following figure shows a sharded table horizontally partitioned across three shards.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A use case is distributing customer account data across multiple physical databases.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, a customer with ID 28459361 may look up his records.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The following figure shows a possible architecture.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The customer request is routed through a connection pool, where sharding directors (network listeners) direct the request to the appropriate shard, which contains all the customer rows.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A database can be considered from both a physical and logical perspective.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Physical data is data viewable at the operating system level.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, operating system utilities such as the Linux `ls` and `ps` can list database files and processes.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Logical data such as a table is meaningful only for the database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A SQL statement can list the tables in an Oracle database, but an operating system utility cannot.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The database has physical structures and logical structures.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Because the physical and logical structures are separate, you can manage the physical storage of data without affecting access to logical storage structures.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For example, renaming a physical database file does not rename the tables whose data is stored in this file.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The physical database structures are the files that store the data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Many other files are important for the functioning of an Oracle database server.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] These include parameter files and networking files.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Backup files and archived redo log files are offline files important for backup and recovery.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Logical storage structures enable Oracle Database to have fine-grained control of disk space use.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An Oracle database uses memory structures and processes to manage and access the database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] All memory structures exist in the main memory of the computers that constitute the RDBMS.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] When applications connect to an Oracle database, they connect to a database instance.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The instance services applications by allocating other memory areas in addition to the SGA, and starting other processes in addition to background processes.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A process is a mechanism in an operating system that can run a series of steps.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Some operating systems use the terms job, task, or thread.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] For the purposes of this topic, a thread is equivalent to a process.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle processes include server processes and background processes.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In most environments, Oracle processes and client processes run on separate computers.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database creates and uses memory structures for program code, data shared among users, and private data areas for each connected user.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] To take full advantage of a given computer system or network, Oracle Database enables processing to be split between the database server and the client programs.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The computer running the RDBMS handles the database server responsibilities while the computers running the applications handle the interpretation and display of data.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The application architecture is the computing environment in which a database application connects to an Oracle database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The two most common database architectures are client/server and multitier.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In a client/server architecture, the client application initiates a request for an operation to be performed on the database server.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The server runs Oracle Database software and handles the functions required for concurrent, shared data access.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The server receives and processes requests that originate from clients.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In a multitier architecture, one or more application servers perform parts of the operation.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An application server contains a large part of the application logic, provides access to the data for the client, and performs some query processing.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] In this way, the load on the database decreases.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] The application server can serve as an interface between clients and multiple databases and provide an additional level of security.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] A service-oriented architecture (SOA) is a multitier architecture in which application functionality is encapsulated in services.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] SOA services are usually implemented as Web services.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Web services are accessible through HTTP and are based on XML-based standards such as Web Services Description Language (WSDL) and SOAP.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Database can act as a Web service provider in a traditional multitier or SOA environment.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Communication protocols define the way that data is transmitted and received on a network.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Net Services supports communications on all major network protocols, including TCP/IP, HTTP, FTP, and WebDAV.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Net, a component of Oracle Net Services, establishes and maintains a network session from a client application to a database server.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] After a network session is established, Oracle Net acts as the data courier for both the client application and the database server, exchanging messages between them.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Oracle Net can perform these jobs because it is located on each computer in the network.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] An important component of Net Services is the Oracle Net Listener (called the listener), which is a process that runs on the database or elsewhere in the network.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] Client applications send connection requests to the listener, which manages the traffic of these requests to the database.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p01] When a connection is established, the client and database communicate directly.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The documentation set is designed with specific access paths to ensure that users are able to find the information they need as efficiently as possible.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The documentation set is divided into three layers or groups: basic, intermediate, and advanced.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] Users begin with the manuals in the basic group, proceed to the manuals in the intermediate group (the 2 Day + series), and finally to the advanced manuals, which include the remainder of the documentation.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] You can find the documentation for supported releases of Oracle Database at https://docs.oracle.com/en/database/oracle/oracle-database/.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] Technical users who are new to Oracle Database begin by reading one or more manuals in the basic group from cover to cover.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] Each manual in this group is designed to be read in two days.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] In addition to this manual, the basic group includes the manuals shown in the following table.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The manuals in the basic group are closely related, which is reflected in the number of cross-references.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] For example, Oracle Database Concepts frequently sends users to a 2 Day manual to learn how to perform a task based on a concept.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The 2 Day manuals frequently reference Oracle Database Concepts for conceptual background about a task.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The next step up from the basic group is the intermediate group.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] Manuals in the intermediate group are prefixed with the word 2 Day + because they expand on and assume information contained in the 2 Day manuals.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The 2 Day + manuals cover topics in more depth than is possible in the basic manuals, or cover topics of special interest.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The advanced group manuals are intended for expert users who require more detailed information about a particular topic than can be provided by the 2 Day + manuals.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The following table lists essential reference manuals in the advanced group.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The advanced guides are too numerous to list in this section.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The following table lists guides that the majority of expert Oracle DBAs use.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] The following table lists guides that the majority of expert Oracle developers use.
[src:oracle-database/introduction-to-oracle-database-p02] Other advanced guides required by a particular user depend on the area of responsibility of this user.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The company sells database software (particularly the Oracle Database), enterprise applications, and cloud infrastructure and hardware.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle's core application software is a suite of enterprise software products, including enterprise resource planning (ERP), human capital management (HCM), customer experience (CX) and supply chain management (SCM) software.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Larry Ellison, Bob Miner, and Ed Oates co-founded Oracle on June 16, 1977, in Santa Clara, California, as **Software Development Laboratories** (**SDL**).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Beginning as consultants with a background in large-scale memory after a project for Ampex, Ellison took inspiration from the 1970 paper written by Edgar F.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Codd on relational database management systems (RDBMS) named "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks." He heard about the IBM System R database from an article in an IBM research journal provided by Oates.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Ellison wanted to make Oracle's product compatible with System R, but failed to do so as IBM kept the error codes for its DBMS a secret.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] SDL changed its name to **Relational Software, Inc** (**RSI**) in 1979, then again to **Oracle Systems Corporation** in 1983, to align itself more closely with its flagship product Oracle Database.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The name also drew from the codename of a 1977 project for the Central Intelligence Agency, Oracle's first customer; the company received permission to use the code name for the new product.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Miner served as a senior programmer, and Oates also worked in development.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The three founders decided that Ellison was the worst programmer so he became the salesman.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Understanding both customers and technology, Ellison designed database tables that he used to demonstrate the power of SQL to customers.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] By February 1983 the *Rosen Electronics Letter* said that Oracle was "the most comprehensive offering we've seen" among databases, with good marketing and a substantial installed base encouraging developers to write software for it.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The newsletter said that revenue in fiscal 1983 would be about $8 million and would double in 1984.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On March 12, 1986, the company had its initial public offering.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 1989, Oracle moved its world headquarters to the Redwood Shores neighborhood of Redwood City, California, though its campus was not completed until 1995.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The company hired so many from top universities that Humphries compared it to "Cargill buying crops".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Some new employees worked as receptionists or distributed coffee until more suitable positions became available.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle in the late 1980s began selling enterprise software running on the database, starting with financial software, then manufacturing.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Many at Oracle wanted to discontinue applications; the first several versions were weak, they competed with the company's independent software vendors and value-added reseller partners, and applications were never profitable for Oracle until after 2000.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Selling them (and acquiring vendors such as JD Edwards and PeopleSoft, the latter being the second hostile takeover in the history of software) nonetheless allowed Oracle to compete with SAP; by the mid-2000s it was the world's largest enterprise software vendor.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 1995, Oracle Systems Corporation changed its name to **Oracle Corporation**, officially named Oracle, but is sometimes referred to as Oracle Corporation, the name of the holding company.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2010, Oracle launched Fusion Applications to unify the features and technologies of acquisitions PeopleSoft, Siebel Systems, and JD Edwards, into a single suite.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On July 15, 2013, Oracle transferred its stock listing from Nasdaq to the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] At the time, it was the largest-ever U.S. market transfer.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2018, Oracle opened a new office in the neighboorhod of East Riverside in southeast Austin, Texas.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In December 2020, Oracle announced that it was moving its world headquarters from Redwood Shores to Austin, Texas.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In an effort to compete with Amazon Web Services and its products, Oracle announced in 2019 it was partnering with former rival Microsoft.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The alliance claimed that Oracle Cloud and Microsoft Azure would be directly connected, allowing customers of each to store data on both cloud computing platforms and run software on either Oracle or Azure.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Some saw this not only as an attempt to compete with Amazon but also with Google and Salesforce, which acquired Looker and Tableau Software, respectively.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2023, Oracle and Microsoft expanded their partnership to deliver Oracle database services on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure running inside Microsoft Azure.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] A year later, Oracle announced similar partnerships with Amazon Web Services and Google Cloud, making the Oracle database available in all four major hyperscaler providers.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In December 2021, Oracle announced the acquisition of Cerner, a health information technology company.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The acquisition of Cerner was completed on June 8, 2022, for US$28.3 billion in cash.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Also in December 2021, Oracle announced the acquisition of Federos, an artificial intelligence (AI) and automation tools company for network performance.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In February 2023, the company announced it was going to invest $1.5 billion into the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, including opening a data center in the country's capital, Riyadh.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In April 2024, Oracle announced it was moving its world headquarters from Austin to a new complex in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In June 2024, Oracle announced a $1 billion investment in Spain to enhance artificial intelligence and cloud computing.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] This investment will create a new cloud region in Madrid in partnership with Telefónica.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The goal is to help Spanish businesses and the public sector with digital transformation and to meet European Union regulations.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The same year, the company announced investments in Japan and Malaysia for US$8 billion and US$6.5 billion, respectively.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In January 2025, President Donald Trump announced Stargate, a joint venture by Oracle, OpenAI, SoftBank and investment firm MGX to invest $500 billion over four years in artificial intelligence infrastructure in the US.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Also in 2025, the company announced additional investments in the United Kingdom, Germany and the Netherlands for US$5 billion and US$3 billion, respectively.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In September 2025, Oracle announced it was promoting Clay Magouyrk, president of cloud infrastructure, and Mike Sicilia, president of industries, to become co-CEOs.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] They replaced Safra Catz, who held the position for 11 years, and transitioned to a new role as executive vice chair.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In January 2026, social media platform TikTok announced it finalized a deal to change ownership of its U.S. operations, with Oracle, MGX and private equity firm Silver Lake each owning a 15% stake in the venture, while ByteDance retained a 19.9% stake.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] As of March 2026, Oracles TikTok stake was worth an estimated ~$2B.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In March 2026, Oracle signed a voluntary "ratepayer protection pledge" where companies pledge to build or buy energy needed to power data centers at a different rate to regular consumers, allowing them to keep utility bills down substantially.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In April 2026, it was reported that Oracle laid off nearly 12,000 staff in India, according to the impacted employees.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The company was believed to be planning another mass layoff round within a month.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] For the second quarter of fiscal year 2026 (ending November 2025), Oracle reported total revenue of $14.1 billion, with cloud infrastructure (IaaS) revenue growing 68% year-over-year to $4.1 billion.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Total remaining performance obligations surged to $130 billion, reflecting strong demand for AI infrastructure capacity.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle provides cloud infrastructure, AI services, database and database management software, enterprise applications, analytics, and developer tools that help businesses manage their data, operations, and IT environments.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle provides software applications, such as integrated enterprise software applications, Oracle Fusion Cloud Applications, human capital management (HCM), customer relationship management (CRM), and supply chain management (SCM).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The Oracle Database was released in 2004 as 10g.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Subsequently, the product was released several times, with the newest issue released as 12c in 2018.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle released its Autonomous Database in 2018, Oracle Database 23ai in 2024, and issued its newest release Oracle AI Database 26ai in 2025.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Fusion Middleware is a family of middleware software products, including application server, system integration, business process management (BPM), user interaction, content management, identity management and business intelligence (BI) products.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Applications, software sold by Oracle based on its own database, first appeared in the late 1980s.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Enterprise Manager (OEM) is a web-based monitoring and management tool for Oracle products (and for some third-party software), including database management, middleware management, application management, hardware and virtualization management and cloud management.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The Primavera products of Oracle's Construction & Engineering Global Business Unit (CEGBU) consist of project-management software.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation develops and supports two operating systems: Oracle Solaris and Oracle Linux.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Cloud is a cloud computing service offered by Oracle Corporation providing servers, storage, network, applications and services through a global network of Oracle Corporation managed data centers.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The company allows these services to be provisioned on demand over the Internet.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Cloud provides Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), Software as a Service (SaaS) and Data as a Service (DaaS).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] These services are used to build, deploy, integrate and extend applications in the cloud.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle has continued to make updates to its generative AI service, which is built and supported on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure and large language models (LLM) from Cohere as of 2023, Meta's Llama as of 2024, and xAI's Grok 3 as of 2025.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The company has also been working to integrate generative AI into its other services.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In April 2025, Oracle incorporated HeatWave GenAI into its database.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In September 2025, Oracle and OpenAI signed a $300 billion contract for 4.5 gigawatts of power capacity over five years.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In October 2025, Oracle and Microsoft announced a partnership to enhance supply chain efficiency and responsiveness for manufacturers.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] It was also announced that Oracle will offer cloud services using Advanced Micro Devices' upcoming MI450 artificial intelligence chips.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] OPERA Cloud is a property management software (PMS) positioned under Oracle Hospitality.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] It's available across 236 countries and territories.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2026, IHG Hotels & Resorts onboarded OPERA Cloud as its official PMS.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2025, Accor onboarded it as its official PMS, moving away from Mews (software).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2023, it was a market leader among PMSs.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 1990, Oracle laid off 10% (about 400 people) of its work force because of accounting errors.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] This crisis came about because of Oracle's "up-front" marketing strategy, in which sales people urged potential customers to buy the largest possible amount of software all at once.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The sales people then booked the value of future license sales in the current quarter, thereby increasing their bonuses.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] This became a problem when the future sales subsequently failed to materialize.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle eventually had to restate its earnings twice, and also settled (out of court) class-action lawsuits arising from its having overstated its earnings.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Ellison stated in 1992 that Oracle had made "an incredible business mistake".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Humphries described the cause ("building for years") as a combination of technical problems that benefited rivals, and the sales force using side letters and other improper tactics to meet the company's longstanding goal of doubling revenue each year.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Ellison hired ("bring in adults", Jerry Held said) new executives Jeff Henley and Raymond J.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Lane, who helped the company recover from what Ken Jacobs later described as a "near death experience", in which Oracle required an investment from a Japanese steel company to meet payroll.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The relational database industry was unusually concentrated.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Besides being headquartered near each other in the San Francisco Bay area, database technology experts attended the same universities and served on the same standards committees (with Jim Gray serving as neutral arbiter as companies tried to get competing proposals enacted).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Sales and marketing people were both fierce rivals and often moved between the companies, even as engineers socialized with each other.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The smaller, later-founded database vendors viewed Oracle as their top enemy, with Bob MacDonald of Informix Software calling Oracle "the evil empire", while Humphries described his company as "the Klingons of" the bay.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Held later described his company's philosophy as "it's not good enough for Oracle to win.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] It was important for somebody else to lose".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Ingres was its first major competitor; Oracle's strategy of focusing on one opponent at a time.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Even publicly complimenting other rivals "to take the pressure off", Held said, while effective, caused it to neglect Sybase as a threat.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Conversely, when Sybase had technical problems "it was: how do you put every ounce of product marketing, sales effort and focus on that".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] IBM's endorsement of SQL in Db2 in the early 1980s benefited Oracle and forced rivals like Ingres and Informix Corporation to adopt SQL to compete.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle acknowledged IBM as the standard while emphasizing its own superiority, touting "total IBM SQL compatibility" while IBM's software ran "*only on IBM mainframes*".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] By the mid-1980s the company described its database as "the last DBMS", bragging that Oracle now had larger database revenue than dBASE maker Ashton-Tate, and stating that Microsoft, Ashton-Tate, and Sybase's planned Microsoft SQL Server "jumped on Oracle's SQL bandwagon".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] MacDonald credited Oracle with "being marketing oriented before any of the competitors ... pushing the envelope on selling the future way ahead of the rest of us".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Stu Schuster of Sybase said "Larry taught us a lot about marketing".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] While other database companies' brochures emphasized technical features, Oracle advertisements showed an Oracle jet fighter shooting down Ashton-Tate and Borland biplanes; dBASE, IBM, and Db2 were among the many competitors Oracle marketing criticized by name.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Conversely, another Oracle ad quoted Microsoft's Bill Gates, Sun's Scott McNealy, Hewlett-Packard's John A.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Young, and Apple Computer's John Sculley as agreeing with Ellison on Oracle's database breakthroughs.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Larry Rowe of Ingres said "you could never come up with a strategy to beat Oracle because whatever you said today, two days later Ellison was saying it with more marketing dollars".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Schuster and Held recalled "a not very pleasant environment because it was so directly competitive".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Even IBM participated in the "billboard wars".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] By 1995 Oracle had 44% of the $2.4 billion relational database market; Sybase had 17% and Informix had 16%.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] By 1996 Informix, after acquiring Illustra, became Oracle's most important rival.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The intense war between Informix CEO Phil White and Ellison made front-page news in Silicon Valley for three years.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Informix claimed that Oracle had hired away Informix engineers to disclose important trade secrets about an upcoming product.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Informix finally dropped its lawsuit against Oracle in 1997.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In November 2005, a book detailing the war between Oracle and Informix was published, titled *The Real Story of Informix Software and Phil White*.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] It gave a detailed chronology of the battle of Informix against Oracle, and how Informix Software's CEO Phil White landed in jail because of his obsession with overtaking Ellison.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle has competed for new database licenses on UNIX, GNU, and Windows operating systems primarily against IBM's Db2 and Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2004, Oracle's sales grew at a rate of 14.5% to $6.2 billion, giving it 41.3% and the top share of the relational-database market (*InformationWeek* – March 2005), with market share estimated at up to 44.6% in 2005 by some sources.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation's main competitors in the database arena remain IBM Db2 and Microsoft SQL Server, and to a lesser extent Sybase and Teradata, with free databases such as PostgreSQL and MySQL also having a significant share of the market.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] EnterpriseDB, based on PostgreSQL, has recently made inroads by proclaiming that its product delivers Oracle-compatible SQL and procedural language features at a much lower price-point.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle's main competitors in the database market include IBM and Microsoft, and in enterprise applications, SAP.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On March 22, 2007, Oracle sued SAP, accusing it of fraud and unfair competition.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In the market for business intelligence software, many other software companies, both small and large, have successfully competed in quality with Oracle and SAP products.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Business intelligence vendors can be categorized into the "big four" consolidated BI firms such as Oracle, who has entered BI market through a recent trend of acquisitions (including Hyperion Solutions), and the independent "pure play" vendors such as MicroStrategy, Actuate, and SAS.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Financials was ranked in the Top 20 Most Popular Accounting Software Infographic by Capterra in 2014, beating out SAP and a number of its other competitors.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] From 1988, Oracle Corporation and the German company SAP AG had a decade-long history of cooperation, beginning with the integration of SAP's R/3 enterprise application suite with Oracle's relational database products.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Despite the SAP partnership with Microsoft, and the increasing integration of SAP applications with Microsoft products (such as Microsoft SQL Server, a competitor to Oracle Database), Oracle and SAP continue their cooperation.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] According to Oracle Corporation, the majority of SAP's customers use Oracle databases.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2004, Oracle began to increase its interest in the enterprise-applications market (in 1989, Oracle had already released Oracle Financials).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] A series of acquisitions by Oracle Corporation began, most notably with those of PeopleSoft, Siebel Systems, and Hyperion.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] SAP recognized that Oracle had started to become a competitor in a market where SAP had the leadership, and saw an opportunity to lure in customers from those companies that Oracle Corporation had acquired.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] SAP would offer those customers special discounts on the licenses for its enterprise applications.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle and SAP (the latter through its recently acquired subsidiary TomorrowNow) competed in the third-party enterprise software maintenance and support market.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On March 22, 2007, Oracle filed a lawsuit against SAP.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] SAP AG Oracle alleged that TomorrowNow, which provides discount support for legacy Oracle product lines, used the accounts of former Oracle customers to systematically download patches and support documents from Oracle's website and to appropriate them for SAP's use.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Some analysts have suggested the suit could form part of a strategy by Oracle Corporation to decrease competition with SAP in the market for third-party enterprise software maintenance and support.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On July 3, 2007, SAP admitted that TomorrowNow employees had made "inappropriate downloads" from the Oracle support website.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] However, it claims that SAP personnel and SAP customers had no access to Oracle intellectual property via TomorrowNow.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] SAP's CEO Henning Kagermann stated that "Even a single inappropriate download is unacceptable from my perspective.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] We regret very much that this occurred." Additionally, SAP announced that it had "instituted changes" in TomorrowNow's operational oversight.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On November 23, 2010, a U.S. district court jury in Oakland, California, found that SAP AG must pay Oracle Corp $1.3 billion for copyright infringement, awarding damages that could be the largest-ever for copyright infringement.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] While admitting liability, SAP estimated the damages at no more than $40 million, while Oracle claimed that they are at least $1.65 billion.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The awarded amount is one of the 10 or 20 largest jury verdicts in U.S. legal history.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] SAP said it was disappointed by the verdict and might appeal.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On September 1, 2011, a federal judge overturned the judgment and offered a reduced amount or a new trial, calling Oracle's original award "grossly" excessive.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On August 3, 2012, SAP and Oracle agreed on a judgment for $306 million in damages, pending approval from the U.S. district court judge, "to save time and expense of [a] new trial".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] After the accord has been approved, Oracle can ask a federal appeals court to reinstate the earlier jury verdict.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In addition to the damages payment, SAP has already paid Oracle $120 million for its legal fees.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] 82 in the 2018 Fortune 500 list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] According to Bloomberg, Oracle's CEO-to-employee pay ratio is 1,205:1.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle is one of the approved employers of ACCA and the median employee compensation rate was $89,887.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2000, Oracle attracted attention from the computer industry and the press after hiring private investigators to uncover unfavorable information from organizations sympathetic to rival Microsoft.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] During the investigation, Oracle was accused of attempting to purchase trash from a janitor at the Association for Competitive Technology.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] This resulted in an antitrust trial against Microsoft.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The Chairman of Oracle Corporation, Larry Ellison, defended his company's hiring of an East Coast detective agency, calling the snooping a "public service".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The investigation reportedly included a $1,200 offer to janitors at the Association for Competitive Technology to look through Microsoft's trash.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2002, Oracle Corporation marketed many of its products using the slogan "Can't break it, can't break in", or "Unbreakable".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] However, two weeks after its introduction, David Litchfield, Alexander Kornbrust, Cesar Cerrudo and others demonstrated a suite of successful attacks against Oracle products.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation's chief security officer Mary Ann Davidson said that, rather than representing a literal claim of Oracle's products' impregnability, she saw the campaign in the context of fourteen independent security evaluations that Oracle Corporation's database server had passed.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2004, then-United States Attorney General John Ashcroft sued Oracle Corporation to prevent it from acquiring a multibillion-dollar intelligence contract.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] After Ashcroft's resignation from government, he founded a lobbying firm, The Ashcroft Group, which Oracle hired in 2005.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] With the group's help, Oracle went on to acquire the contract.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation was awarded a contract by the State of Oregon's Oregon Health Authority (OHA) to develop Cover Oregon, the state's healthcare exchange website, as part of the U.S.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] When the site tried to go live on October 1, 2013, it failed, and registrations had to be taken using paper applications until the site could be fixed.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In August 2014, Oracle Corporation sued Cover Oregon for breach of contract, and then later that month the state of Oregon sued Oracle Corporation, in a civil complaint for breach of contract, fraud, filing false claims and "racketeering".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In September 2016, the two sides reached a settlement valued at over $100 million to the state, and a six-year agreement for Oracle to continue modernizing state software and IT.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In August 2022, a class action lawsuit was filed against Oracle by the law firm Lieff Cabraser.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The lawsuit alleged that Oracle engaged in "deliberate and purposeful surveillance of the general population via their digital and online existence", specifically focusing on Oracle operating a surveillance machine that tracked and recorded personal data in real-time.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The litigants alleged that through such surveillance, the company violated the Federal Electronic Communications Privacy Act, California's state constitution, the California Invasion of Privacy Act, competition law, and California Common Law.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The lawsuit was settled in July 2024 for $115 million.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Between 2011 and 2024, Oracle was investigated for engaging in bribery practices that violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act across its subsidiaries in South Africa, India, Turkey, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In all instances, the company settled with the United States Securities and Exchange Commission.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Following the beginning of the Gaza war in 2023, Oracle's top executives, including Safra Catz and Larry Ellison, publicly aligned the company with Israel's military operations.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] They issued statements of solidarity, paid double salaries to Israeli employees, and donated to organizations connected to Israel's wartime response.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2024, Catz said to Israeli business news outlet CTech, "For employees, it's clear: if you're not for America or Israel, don't work here".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2025, *The Intercept* spoke with Oracle employees who supported Palestine, but were afraid to speak out in their workplace.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Sixty-eight Oracle employees signed an open letter criticizing the company's ties to Israel.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On July 29, 2010, the United States Department of Justice (DoJ) filed suit against Oracle Corporation alleging fraud.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The lawsuit argues that the government received deals inferior to those Oracle gave to its commercial clients.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The DoJ added its heft to an already existing whistleblower lawsuit filed by Paul Frascella, who was once senior director of contract services at Oracle.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle, the plaintiff, acquired ownership of the Java computer programming language when it acquired Sun Microsystems in January 2010.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The Java software includes sets of pre-developed software code to allow programs and apps to accomplish common tasks in a consistent manner.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The pre-developed code is organized into separate "packages" which each contain a set of "classes".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Each class contains numerous methods, which instruct a program or app to do a certain task.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Software developers "became accustomed to using Java's designations at the package, class, and method level".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle and Google (the defendant) tried to negotiate an agreement for Oracle to license Java to Google, which would have allowed Google to use Java in developing programs for mobile devices using the Android operating system.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] However, the two companies never reached an agreement.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] After negotiations failed, Google created its own programming platform, which was based on Java, and contained 37 copied Java packages as well as new packages developed by Google.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On June 15, 2011, HP filed a lawsuit in California Superior Court in Santa Clara, claiming that Oracle had breached an agreement to support the Itanium microprocessor used in HP's high-end enterprise servers.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle called the lawsuit "an abuse of the judicial process" and said that had it known SAP's Léo Apotheker was about to be hired as HP's new CEO, any support for HP's Itanium servers would not have been implied.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On August 1, 2012, a California judge said in a tentative ruling that Oracle must continue porting its software at no cost until HP discontinues its sales of Itanium-based servers.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] HP was awarded $3 billion in damages against Oracle in 2016.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] HP argued Oracle's canceling support damaged HP's Itanium server brand.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle had announced that it would appeal both the decision and damages, but the decision stayed.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On April 20, 2012, the US General Services Administration banned Oracle from the most popular portal for bidding on GSA contracts for undisclosed reasons.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle has previously used this portal for around four hundred million dollars a year in revenue.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 2011, Oracle settled with the General Services Administration for $199.5 million in a lawsuit filed under the False Claims Act.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In January 2010, Oracle completed its acquisition of Sun Microsystems, valued at more than $7 billion, a move that transformed Oracle from solely a software company to a manufacturer of both software and hardware.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The acquisition was delayed for several months by the European Commission because of concerns about MySQL, but was unconditionally approved in the end.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] State Department Embassy cables were leaked to WikiLeaks.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] One cable revealed that the U.S. pressured the E.U. to allow Oracle to acquire Sun.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The Sun acquisition was closely watched by free software users and some companies, due to the fear that Oracle might end Sun's traditional support of free projects.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Since the acquisition, Oracle has discontinued OpenSolaris and StarOffice, and sued Google over the Java patents Oracle acquired from Sun.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On December 20, 2021, Oracle announced that it agreed to acquire Cerner Corporation (now *Oracle Health* and *Oracle Life Sciences*) for approximately US$28.3 billion, creating a dedicated Industry Business Unit within the company.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Cerner is the largest international supplier of health information technology, such as electronic health records (EHR), revenue cycle solutions, and biomedical device integration platforms, and has its headquarters in Kansas City, Missouri, US.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The deal closed in early July 2022 after receiving final approval from European regulators, making it Oracle's largest acquisition and one of the largest in corporate history.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle's purchase of Cerner was part of an effort to introduce Oracle products into the healthcare market, particularly in the United States although Oracle plans to expand Cerner's global operations.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In September 2024, Oracle announced new investments and the release of Oracle Clinical Digital Assistant, a generative AI system that automatically creates consultation documentation and proposes orders.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In March 2025, a threat actor claimed to have stolen 6 million data records from Oracle Health (formerly Cerner).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle claimed that its Oracle Cloud Infrastructure was not breached and that no customer data from it was exposed.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Some legacy Cerner servers experienced unauthorized access, but Oracle has not confirmed the scale of impact.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In April 2025, the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) issued a warning to Oracle customers to secure their environments.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On September 13, 2020, Bloomberg News reported that Oracle won a bidding war with other U.S.-based companies to take over social media company TikTok's operations in the United States following the company's pressure to forcibly be shut down by the Trump administration.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle was described as a "trusted tech partner" by TikTok.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] On September 19, 2020, the Trump administration approved of the sale of TikTok's US operations to Oracle "[delaying] — by one week — restrictions that were originally to take effect" on September 20 as indicated by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] As September 25, 2025, TikTok was bought by Silver Lake and Abu Dhabi's MGX.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle will own 45% of the app in the US, and ByteDance 35% after delays with the ban for the 4th time.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle will store data of US TikTok users on its cloud computers, and it will be involved in the new TikTok spinoff's cybersecurity.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle partnered with the arms company Anduril Industries to provide their Lattice military software platform to the governments of United States, United Kingdom and Australia.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation's world headquarters are located in Austin, Texas.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In April 2024, Oracle announced plans to build its largest office hub, with 8,500 jobs, in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle has a large office complex located on the San Francisco Peninsula in the Redwood Shores area of Redwood City.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] This complex was home to Oracle world headquarters from 1989 to 2020.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] It is located on the former site of Marine World/Africa USA, which moved from Redwood Shores to Vallejo in 1986.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation originally leased two buildings on the Oracle Parkway site, moving its finance and administration departments from the corporation's former headquarters on Davis Drive, Belmont, California.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Eventually, Oracle purchased the complex and constructed four additional buildings.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The distinctive Oracle Parkway buildings, nicknamed the Emerald City, served as sets for the futuristic headquarters of the fictional company "NorthAm Robotics" in the Robin Williams film *Bicentennial Man* (1999).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The campus also represented the headquarters of Cyberdyne Systems in the movie *Terminator Genisys* (2015).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation operates in multiple markets and has acquired many companies to help it do so.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In some cases these companies became the starting points for global business units (GBUs) targeting particular vertical markets.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In 1994 and 1995, Oracle sponsored Benetton Formula.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] From 2001 to 2021, Sean Tucker's stunt biplane was sponsored by Oracle and performed frequently at air shows around the US.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In October 2006, the Golden State Warriors and the Oracle Corporation announced a 10-year agreement in which the Oakland Arena would become known as the Oracle Arena.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The agreement ended after the 2018–2019 NBA season when the Warriors relocated to the Chase Center in San Francisco.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] In January 2019, the San Francisco Giants entered into a 20-year agreement to rename its stadium Oracle Park.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] Larry Ellison's sailing team competes as Oracle Team USA.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] The team won the America's Cup twice, in 2010 (as BMW Oracle Racing) and in 2013, despite being penalized for cheating.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-corporation] From the 2022 Formula One season, Oracle signed a five-year deal worth $500 million to become title sponsors of Red Bull Racing, after already being a sponsor effective from the 2021 season.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] It is commonly used for online transaction processing (OLTP), data warehousing (DW), and mixed database workloads.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] As a converged database, it supports multiple data models within a single engine, including relational, JSON document, XML, spatial, graph, text, and vector data, all queryable through SQL.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Oracle Database runs on-premises, on Oracle engineered systems such as Oracle Exadata, on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, and as a managed Autonomous Database service.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] It is also offered inside Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud, and Amazon Web Services data centers through Oracle's multicloud offerings.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] The current long-term release is Oracle AI Database 26ai, which was introduced in October 2025.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Larry Ellison and his two friends and former co-workers, Bob Miner and Ed Oates, started a consultancy called Software Development Laboritories (SDL) in 1977, later Oracle Corporation.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] SDL developed the original version of the Oracle software.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] The name *Oracle* comes from the code-name of a Central Intelligence Agency-funded project Ellison has worked on while formerly employed by Ampex; the CIA was Oracle's first customer, and allowed the company to use the code name for the new product.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Ellison wanted his database to be compatible with IBM System R, but that company's Don Chamberlin declined to release its error codes.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] By 1985 Oracle advertised, however, that "Programs written for SQL/DS or DB2 will run unmodified" on the many non-IBM mainframes, minicomputers, and microcomputers its database supported "Because all versions of ORACLE *are* identical".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Oracle Corporation held its initial public offering on March 12, 1986.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] The company grew rapidly during the 1980s, though a financial setback in 1990 led to its first quarterly loss and significant layoffs before the business recovered.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Oracle7, released in 1992, matured the product into a leading enterprise relational database management system, adding persistent PL/SQL stored procedures and triggers, a cost-based query optimizer, and improved administration tools.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Oracle Database 12c (2013) introduced the multitenant architecture and the In-Memory Column Store, with "c" denoting "cloud".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] In 2017 Oracle announced Oracle Autonomous Database, a self-managing cloud service, with the first services becoming available in 2018.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Beyond the on-premises editions, Oracle Autonomous Database automates provisioning, tuning, patching, and scaling and is offered in data-warehousing and transaction-processing variants.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Oracle products follow a custom release-numbering and -naming convention.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] The "ai" in the current release, Oracle AI Database 26ai, stands for "Artificial Intelligence".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Oracle Database 19c, 10g, and Oracle9i Database) have used suffixes of "c", "g", and "i" which stand for "Cloud", "Grid", and "Internet" respectively.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Prior to the release of Oracle8i Database, no suffixes featured in Oracle AI Database naming conventions.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] There was no v1 of Oracle AI Database, as Ellison "knew no one would want to buy version 1".
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] For some database releases, Oracle also provides an Express Edition (XE) that is free to use.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] The Introduction to Oracle AI Database includes a brief history on some of the key innovations introduced with each major release of Oracle AI Database.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] See My Oracle Support (MOS) note *Release Schedule of Current Database Releases (Doc ID 742060.1)* for the current Oracle AI Database releases and their patching end dates.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Prior to Oracle Database 18c, Oracle Corporation released Critical Patch Updates (CPUs) and Security Patch Updates (SPUs) and Security Alerts to close security vulnerabilities.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] These releases are issued quarterly; some of these releases have updates issued prior to the next quarterly release.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] Starting with Oracle Database 18c, Oracle Corporation releases Release Updates (RUs) and Release Update Revisions (RURs).
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] RUs usually contain security, regression (bug), optimizer, and functional fixes which may include feature extensions as well.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] RURs include all fixes from their corresponding RU but only add new security and regression fixes.
[src:oracle-database/oracle-database] However, no new optimizer or functional fixes are included.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL includes procedural language elements such as conditions and loops, and can handle exceptions (run-time errors).
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] It allows the declaration of constants and variables, procedures, functions, packages, types and variables of those types, and triggers.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Arrays are supported involving the use of PL/SQL collections.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Implementations from version 8 of Oracle Database onwards have included features associated with object-orientation.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] One can create PL/SQL units such as procedures, functions, packages, types, and triggers, which are stored in the database for reuse by applications that use any of the Oracle Database programmatic interfaces.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The first public version of the PL/SQL definition was in 1995.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The main feature of SQL (non-procedural) is also its drawback: control statements (decision-making or iterative control) cannot be used if only SQL is to be used.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL provides the functionality of other procedural programming languages, such as decision making, iteration etc.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A PL/SQL program unit is one of the following: PL/SQL anonymous block, procedure, function, package specification, package body, trigger, type specification, type body, library.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Program units are the PL/SQL source code that is developed, compiled, and ultimately executed on the database.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The basic unit of a PL/SQL source program is the block, which groups together related declarations and statements.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A PL/SQL block is defined by the keywords DECLARE, BEGIN, EXCEPTION, and END.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] These keywords divide the block into a declarative part, an executable part, and an exception-handling part.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The declaration section is optional and may be used to define and initialize constants and variables.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] If a variable is not initialized then it defaults to NULL value.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The optional exception-handling part is used to handle run-time errors.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The symbol `:=` functions as an assignment operator to store a value in a variable.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Blocks can be nested – i.e., because a block is an executable statement, it can appear in another block wherever an executable statement is allowed.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A block can be submitted to an interactive tool (such as SQL*Plus) or embedded within an Oracle Precompiler or OCI program.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The interactive tool or program runs the block once.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The block is not stored in the database, and for that reason, it is called an anonymous block (even if it has a label).
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The purpose of a PL/SQL function is generally used to compute and return a single value.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] This returned value may be a single scalar value (such as a number, date or character string) or a single collection (such as a nested table or array).
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] User-defined functions supplement the built-in functions provided by Oracle Corporation.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A function should only use the default IN type of parameter.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The only out value from the function should be the value it returns.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Procedures resemble functions in that they are named program units that can be invoked repeatedly.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The primary difference is that **functions can be used in a SQL statement whereas procedures cannot**.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Another difference is that the procedure can return multiple values whereas a function should only return a single value.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The procedure begins with a mandatory heading part to hold the procedure name and optionally the procedure parameter list.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Next come the declarative, executable and exception-handling parts, as in the PL/SQL Anonymous Block.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The example above shows a standalone procedure - this type of procedure is created and stored in a database schema using the CREATE PROCEDURE statement.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A procedure may also be created in a PL/SQL package - this is called a Package Procedure.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A procedure created in a PL/SQL anonymous block is called a nested procedure.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The standalone or package procedures, stored in the database, are referred to as "stored procedures".
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Procedures can have three types of parameters: IN, OUT and IN OUT.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The program assigns the parameter value and that value is returned to the calling program.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] An IN OUT parameter may or may not have an initial value.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] That initial value may or may not be modified by the called program.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Any changes made to the parameter are returned to the calling program by default by copying but - with the NO-COPY hint - may be passed by reference.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL also supports external procedures via the Oracle database's standard `ext-proc` process.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Packages are groups of conceptually linked functions, procedures, variables, PL/SQL table and record TYPE statements, constants, cursors, etc.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The use of packages promotes re-use of code.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Packages are composed of the package specification and an optional package body.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The specification is the interface to the application; it declares the types, variables, constants, exceptions, cursors, and subprograms available.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The body fully defines cursors and subprograms, and so implements the specification.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Using package variables one can declare session level (scoped) variables since variables declared in the package specification have a session scope.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A database trigger is like a stored procedure that Oracle Database invokes automatically whenever a specified event occurs.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] It is a named PL/SQL unit that is stored in the database and can be invoked repeatedly.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Unlike a stored procedure, you can enable and disable a trigger, but you cannot explicitly invoke it.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] While a trigger is enabled, the database automatically invokes it—that is, the trigger fires—whenever its triggering event occurs.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] While a trigger is disabled, it does not fire.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] You create a trigger with the CREATE TRIGGER statement.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] You specify the triggering event in terms of triggering statements, and the item they act on.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The trigger is said to be created on or defined on the item—which is either a table, a view, a schema, or the database.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] You also specify the timing point, which determines whether the trigger fires before or after the triggering statement runs and whether it fires for each row that the triggering statement affects.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] If the trigger is created on a table or view, then the triggering event is composed of DML statements, and the trigger is called a DML trigger.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] If the trigger is created on a schema or the database, then the triggering event is composed of either DDL or database operation statements, and the trigger is called a system trigger.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] An INSTEAD OF trigger is either: A DML trigger created on a view or a system trigger defined on a CREATE statement.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The database fires the INSTEAD OF trigger instead of running the triggering statement.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The major datatypes in PL/SQL include NUMBER, CHAR, VARCHAR2, DATE and TIMESTAMP.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] To define a numeric variable, the programmer appends the variable type **NUMBER** to the name definition.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] To specify the (optional) precision (P) and the (optional) scale (S), one can further append these in round brackets, separated by a comma.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A selection of other data-types for numeric variables would include: binary_float, binary_double, dec, decimal, double precision, float, integer, int, numeric, real, small-int, binary_integer.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] To define a character variable, the programmer normally appends the variable type VARCHAR2 to the name definition.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] There follows in brackets the maximum number of characters the variable can store.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Other datatypes for character variables include: varchar, char, long, raw, long raw, nchar, nchar2, clob, blob, and bfile.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Date variables can contain date and time.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The time may be left out, but there is no way to define a variable that only contains the time.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] But there is no TIMESTAMP type that can contain fine-grained timestamp up to millisecond or nanosecond.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The `TO_DATE` function can be used to convert strings to date values.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] To convert the dates to strings one uses the function `TO_CHAR (date_string, format_string)`.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL also supports the use of ANSI date and interval literals.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Exceptions—errors during code execution—are of two types: user-defined and predefined.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Oracle Corporation has *predefined* several exceptions like `NO_DATA_FOUND`, `TOO_MANY_ROWS`, *etc.* Each exception has an SQL error number and SQL error message associated with it.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Programmers can access these by using the `SQLCODE` and `SQLERRM` functions.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] This syntax defines a variable of the type of the referenced column on the referenced tables.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] This sample program defines its own datatype, called *t_address*, which contains the fields *name, street, street_number* and *postcode*.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] So according to the example, we are able to copy the data from the database to the fields in the program.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Using this datatype the programmer has defined a variable called *v_address* and loaded it with data from the ADDRESS table.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The following code segment shows the IF-THEN-ELSIF-ELSE construct.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The ELSIF and ELSE parts are optional so it is possible to create simpler IF-THEN or, IF-THEN-ELSE constructs.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The CASE statement simplifies some large IF-THEN-ELSIF-ELSE structures.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL refers to arrays as "collections".
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Programmers must specify an upper limit for varrays, but need not for index-by tables or for nested tables.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The language includes several collection methods used to manipulate collection elements: for example FIRST, LAST, NEXT, PRIOR, EXTEND, TRIM, DELETE, etc.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Index-by tables can be used to simulate associative arrays, as in this example of a memo function for Ackermann's function in PL/SQL.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] With index-by tables, the array can be indexed by numbers or strings.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] It parallels a Java *map*, which comprises key-value pairs.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] There is only one dimension and it is unbounded.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] With nested tables the programmer needs to understand what is nested.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Here, a new type is created that may be composed of a number of components.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] That type can then be used to make a column in a table, and nested within that column are those components.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] With Varrays you need to understand that the word "variable" in the phrase "variable-size arrays" doesn't apply to the size of the array in the way you might think that it would.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The size the array is declared with is in fact fixed.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The number of elements in the array is variable up to the declared size.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Arguably then, variable-sized arrays aren't that variable in size.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A cursor is a pointer to a private SQL area that stores information coming from a SELECT or data manipulation language (DML) statement (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, or MERGE).
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] A cursor holds the rows (one or more) returned by a SQL statement.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The set of rows the cursor holds is referred to as the active set.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] In a FOR loop, an explicit cursor shall be used if the query will be reused, otherwise an implicit cursor is preferred.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] If using a cursor inside a loop, use a FETCH is recommended when needing to bulk collect or when needing dynamic SQL.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] As a procedural language by definition, PL/SQL provides several iteration constructs, including basic LOOP statements, WHILE loops, FOR loops, and Cursor FOR loops.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Since Oracle 7.3 the REF CURSOR type was introduced to allow recordsets to be returned from stored procedures and functions.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Oracle 9i introduced the predefined SYS_REFCURSOR type, meaning we no longer have to define our own REF CURSOR types.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Loops can be terminated by using the `EXIT` keyword, or by raising an exception.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Cursor-for loops automatically open a cursor, read in their data and close the cursor again.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] As an alternative, the PL/SQL programmer can pre-define the cursor's SELECT-statement in advance to (for example) allow re-use or make the code more understandable (especially useful in the case of long or complex queries).
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] While programmers can readily embed Data Manipulation Language (DML) statements directly into PL/SQL code using straightforward SQL statements, Data Definition Language (DDL) requires more complex "Dynamic SQL" statements in the PL/SQL code.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] However, DML statements underpin the majority of PL/SQL code in typical software applications.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] In the case of PL/SQL dynamic SQL, early versions of the Oracle Database required the use of a complicated Oracle `DBMS_SQL` package library.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] More recent versions have however introduced a simpler "Native Dynamic SQL", along with an associated `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE` syntax.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL works analogously to the embedded procedural languages associated with other relational databases.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] For example, Sybase ASE and Microsoft SQL Server have Transact-SQL, PostgreSQL has PL/pgSQL (which emulates PL/SQL to an extent), MariaDB includes a PL/SQL compatibility parser, and IBM Db2 includes SQL Procedural Language, which conforms to the ISO SQL’s SQL/PSM standard.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The designers of PL/SQL modeled its syntax on that of Ada.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Both Ada and PL/SQL have Pascal as a common ancestor, and so PL/SQL also resembles Pascal in most aspects.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] However, the structure of a PL/SQL package does not resemble the basic Object Pascal program structure as implemented by a Borland Delphi or Free Pascal unit.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Programmers can define public and private global data-types, constants, and static variables in a PL/SQL package.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL also allows for the definition of classes and instantiating these as objects in PL/SQL code.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] This resembles usage in object-oriented programming languages like Object Pascal, C++ and Java.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL refers to a class as an "Abstract Data Type" (ADT) or "User Defined Type" (UDT), and defines it as an Oracle SQL data-type as opposed to a PL/SQL user-defined type, allowing its use in both the Oracle SQL Engine and the Oracle PL/SQL engine.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The constructor and methods of an Abstract Data Type are written in PL/SQL.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The resulting Abstract Data Type can operate as an object class in PL/SQL.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Such objects can also persist as column values in Oracle database tables.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] PL/SQL is fundamentally distinct from Transact-SQL, despite superficial similarities.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Porting code from one to the other usually involves non-trivial work, not only due to the differences in the feature sets of the two languages, but also due to the very significant differences in the way Oracle and SQL Server deal with concurrency and locking.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] The *StepSqlite* product is a PL/SQL compiler for the popular small database SQLite which supports a subset of PL/SQL syntax.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Oracle's Berkeley DB 11g R2 release added support for SQL based on the popular SQLite API by including a version of SQLite in Berkeley DB.
[src:oracle-database/pl-sql] Consequently, StepSqlite can also be used as a third-party tool to run PL/SQL code on Berkeley DB.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] A **stored procedure** (also termed **prc**, **proc**, **storp**, **sproc**, **StoPro**, **StoredProc**, **StoreProc**, **sp**, or **SP**) is a subroutine available to applications that access a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Such procedures are stored in the database data dictionary.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Uses for stored procedures include data-validation (integrated into the database) or access-control mechanisms.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Furthermore, stored procedures can consolidate and centralize logic that was originally implemented in applications.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] To save time and memory, extensive or complex processing that requires execution of several SQL statements can be saved into stored procedures, and all applications call the procedures.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] One can use nested stored procedures by executing one stored procedure from within another.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedures may return result sets, i.e., the results of a `SELECT` statement.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Such result sets can be processed using cursors, by other stored procedures, by associating a result-set locator, or by applications.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedures may also contain declared variables for processing data and cursors that allow it to loop through multiple rows in a table.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored-procedure flow-control statements typically include `IF`, `WHILE`, `LOOP`, `REPEAT`, and `CASE` statements, and more.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can receive variables, return results or modify variables and return them, depending on how and where the variable is declared.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedures are similar to user-defined functions (UDFs).
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] The major difference is that UDFs can be used like any other expression within SQL statements, whereas stored procedures must be invoked using the `CALL` statement.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] The exact and correct implementation of stored procedures varies from one database system to the other.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Most major database vendors support them in some form.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Depending on the database system, stored procedures can be implemented in a variety of programming languages, for example SQL, Java, C, or C++.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedures written in non-SQL languages may or may not execute SQL statements themselves.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] The increasing adoption of stored procedures led to the introduction of procedural elements to the SQL language in the SQL:1999 and SQL:2003 standards in the part SQL/PSM.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] That made SQL an imperative programming language.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Most database systems offer proprietary and vendor-specific extensions, exceeding SQL/PSM.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] A standard specification for Java stored procedures exists as well as SQL/JRT.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] remove all or part of the compiling overhead that is typically needed when software applications send inline (dynamic) SQL queries to a database.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] and other methods to avoid repetitively compiling dynamic SQL statements.) Also, while they avoid some pre-compiled SQL, statements add to the complexity of creating an optimal execution plan because not all arguments of the SQL statement are supplied at compile time.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Depending on the specific database implementation and configuration, mixed performance results will be seen from stored procedures versus generic queries or user defined functions.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] In a production system, this typically means that the procedures run entirely on a specialized database server with direct access to the data.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] The benefit is that it saves network costs, which stands out when a series of SQL statements are involved.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] as an API in the database, which can simplify data management and reduce the need to encode the logic elsewhere in client programs.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] This can result in a lesser likelihood of data corruption by faulty client programs.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] In many systems, stored procedures can be granted access rights to the database that users who execute those procedures do not directly have.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can be used to protect against injection attacks.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedure parameters will be treated as data even if an attacker inserts SQL commands.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Also, some DBMS will check the parameter's type.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] However, a stored procedure that in turn generates dynamic SQL using the input is still vulnerable to SQL injections unless proper precautions are taken.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] In some systems, stored procedures can be used to control transaction management; in others, stored procedures run inside a transaction such that transactions are effectively transparent to them.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Stored procedures can also be invoked from a database trigger or a condition handler.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] For example, a stored procedure may be triggered by an insert on a specific table, or update of a specific field in a table, and the code inside the stored procedure would be executed.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Writing stored procedures as condition handlers also allows database administrators to track errors in the system with greater detail by using stored procedures to catch the errors and record some audit information in the database or an external resource like a file.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Prepared statements take an ordinary statement or query and parameterize it so that different literal values can be used at a later time.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Like stored procedures, they are stored on the server for efficiency and provide some protection from SQL injection attacks.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Although simpler and more declarative, prepared statements are not ordinarily written to use procedural logic and cannot operate on variables.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Because of their simple interface and client-side implementations, prepared statements are more widely reusable between DBMS.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Smart contract is a term applied to executable code stored on a blockchain as opposed to an RDBMS.
[src:oracle-database/stored-procedure] Despite the execution result consensus mechanisms of public blockchain networks differing in principle from traditional private or federated databases, they perform ostensibly the same function as stored procedures, albeit usually with a sense of value transaction.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] This chapter provides an introduction to schema objects and discusses tables, which are the most common types of schema objects.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] A database schema is a logical container for data structures, called schema objects.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Examples of schema objects are tables and indexes.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] You create and manipulate schema objects with SQL.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] A database user account has a password and specific database privileges.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Each user account owns a single schema, which has the same name as the user.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The schema contains the data for the user owning the schema.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] For example, the `hr` user account owns the `hr` schema, which contains schema objects such as the `employees` table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] In a production database, the schema owner usually represents a database application rather than a person.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Within a schema, each schema object of a particular type has a unique name.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] For example, `hr.employees` refers to the table `employees` in the `hr` schema.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Figure 2-1 depicts a schema owner named `hr` and schema objects within the `hr` schema.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Oracle SQL enables you to create and manipulate many other types of schema objects.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The principal types of schema objects are shown in the following table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Other types of objects are also stored in the database and can be created and manipulated with SQL statements but are not contained in a schema.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] These objects include database user account, roles, contexts, and dictionary objects.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Some schema objects store data in a type of logical storage structure called a segment.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] For example, a nonpartitioned heap-organized table or an index creates a segment.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Other schema objects, such as views and sequences, consist of metadata only.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] This topic describes only schema objects that have segments.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Oracle Database stores a schema object logically within a tablespace.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] There is no relationship between schemas and tablespaces: a tablespace can contain objects from different schemas, and the objects for a schema can be contained in different tablespaces.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The data of each object is physically contained in one or more data files.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The following figure shows a possible configuration of table and index segments, tablespaces, and data files.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The data segment for one table spans two data files, which are both part of the same tablespace.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] A segment cannot span multiple tablespaces.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Some schema objects refer to other objects, creating a schema object dependency.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] For example, a view contains a query that references tables or views, while a PL/SQL subprogram invokes other subprograms.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] If the definition of object A references object B, then A is a dependent object on B, and B is a referenced object for A.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Oracle Database provides an automatic mechanism to ensure that a dependent object is always up to date with respect to its referenced objects.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] When you create a dependent object, the database tracks dependencies between the dependent object and its referenced objects.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] When a referenced object changes in a way that might affect a dependent object, the database marks the dependent object invalid.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] For example, if a user drops a table, no view based on the dropped table is usable.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] An invalid dependent object must be recompiled against the new definition of a referenced object before the dependent object is usable.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Recompilation occurs automatically when the invalid dependent object is referenced.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] All Oracle databases include default administrative accounts.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Administrative accounts are highly privileged and are intended only for DBAs authorized to perform tasks such as starting and stopping the database, managing memory and storage, creating and managing database users, and so on.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The `SYS` administrative account is automatically created when a database is created.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] This account can perform all database administrative functions.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The `SYS` schema stores the base tables and views for the data dictionary.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] These base tables and views are critical for the operation of Oracle Database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Tables in the `SYS` schema are manipulated only by the database and must never be modified by any user.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The `SYSTEM` administrative account is also automatically created when a database is created.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The `SYSTEM` schema stores additional tables and views that display administrative information, and internal tables and views used by various Oracle Database options and tools.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Never use the `SYSTEM` schema to store tables of interest to nonadministrative users.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] An Oracle database may include **sample schemas**, which are a set of interlinked schemas that enable Oracle documentation and Oracle instructional materials to illustrate common database tasks.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The `hr` sample schema contains information about employees, departments and locations, work histories, and so on.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] The following illustration depicts an entity-relationship diagram of the tables in `hr`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p01] Most examples in this manual use objects from this schema.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A table is the basic unit of data organization in an Oracle database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A table describes an entity, which is something of significance about which information must be recorded.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, an employee could be an entity.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A table is either permanent or temporary.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A permanent table definition and data persist across sessions.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A temporary table definition persists in the same way as a permanent table definition, but the data exists only for the duration of a transaction or session.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Temporary tables are useful in applications where a result set must be held temporarily, perhaps because the result is constructed by running multiple operations.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A table definition includes a table name and set of columns.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A column identifies an attribute of the entity described by the table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, the column `employee_id` in the `employees` table refers to the employee ID attribute of an employee entity.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In general, you give each column a column name, a data type, and a width when you create a table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, the data type for `employee_id` is `NUMBER(6)`, indicating that this column can only contain numeric data up to 6 digits in width.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The width can be predetermined by the data type, as with `DATE`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A table can contain a **virtual column**, which unlike a nonvirtual column does not consume disk space.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The database derives the values in a virtual column on demand by computing a set of user-specified expressions or functions.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, the virtual column `income` could be a function of the `salary` and `commission_pct` columns.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] An invisible column is a user-specified column whose values are only visible when the column is explicitly specified by name.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] You can add an invisible column to a table without affecting existing applications, and make the column visible if necessary.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In general, invisible columns help migrate and evolve online applications.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A use case might be an application that queries a three-column table with a `SELECT *` statement.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Adding a fourth column to the table would break the application, which expects three columns of data.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Adding a fourth invisible column makes the application function normally.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A developer can then alter the application to handle a fourth column, and make the column visible when the application goes live.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A row is a collection of column information corresponding to a record in a table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, a row in the `employees` table describes the attributes of a specific employee: employee ID, last name, first name, and so on.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] After you create a table, you can insert, query, delete, and update rows using SQL.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The Oracle SQL statement to create a table is `CREATE TABLE`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The following example shows the `CREATE TABLE` statement for the `employees` table in the `hr` sample schema.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The statement specifies columns such as `employee_id`, `first_name`, and so on, specifying a data type such as `NUMBER` or `DATE` for each column.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The following example shows an `ALTER TABLE` statement that adds integrity constraints to the `employees` table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Integrity constraints enforce business rules and prevent the entry of invalid information into tables.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The following sample output shows 8 rows and 6 columns of the `hr.employees` table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Each column has a data type, which is associated with a specific storage format, constraints, and valid range of values.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The data type of a value associates a fixed set of properties with the value.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] These properties cause Oracle Database to treat values of one data type differently from values of another.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, you can multiply values of the `NUMBER` data type, but not values of the `RAW` data type.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] When you create a table, you must specify a data type for each of its columns.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Each value subsequently inserted in a column assumes the column data type.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database provides several built-in data types.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Other important categories of built-in types include raw, large objects (LOBs), and collections.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] PL/SQL has data types for constants and variables, which include `BOOLEAN`, reference types, composite types (records), and user-defined types.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Character data types store alphanumeric data in strings.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The most common character data type is `VARCHAR2`, which is the most efficient option for storing character data.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The byte values correspond to the character encoding scheme, generally called a character set.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The database character set is established at database creation.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Examples of character sets are 7-bit ASCII, EBCDIC, and Unicode UTF-8.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The length semantics of character data types are measurable in bytes or characters.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The treatment of strings as a sequence of bytes is called byte semantics.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] This is the default for character data types.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The treatment of strings as a sequence of characters is called character semantics.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A character is a code point of the database character set.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] data type stores variable-length character literals.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] George Island'`, and `'101'` are all character literals; `5001` is a numeric literal.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Character literals are enclosed in single quotation marks so that the database can distinguish them from schema object names.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] This manual uses the terms text literal, character literal, and string interchangeably.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] When you create a table with a `VARCHAR2` column, you specify a maximum string length.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In Example 2-1, the `last_name` column has a data type of `VARCHAR2(25)`, which means that any name stored in the column has a maximum of 25 bytes.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For each row, Oracle Database stores each value in the column as a variable-length field unless a value exceeds the maximum length, in which case the database returns an error.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, in a single-byte character set, if you enter 10 characters for the `last_name` column value in a row, then the column in the row piece stores only 10 characters (10 bytes), not 25.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Using `VARCHAR2` reduces space consumption.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In contrast to `VARCHAR2`, `CHAR` stores fixed-length character strings.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] When you create a table with a `CHAR` column, the column requires a string length.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The database uses blanks to pad the value to the specified length.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database compares `VARCHAR2` values using nonpadded comparison semantics and compares `CHAR` values using blank-padded comparison semantics.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] data types store Unicode character data.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Unicode is a universal encoded character set that can store information in any language using a single character set.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] `NCHAR` stores fixed-length character strings that correspond to the national character set, whereas `NVARCHAR2` stores variable length character strings.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] You specify a national character set when creating a database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The character set of `NCHAR` and `NVARCHAR2` data types must be either `AL16UTF16` or `UTF8`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Both character sets use Unicode encoding.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] When you create a table with an `NCHAR` or `NVARCHAR2` column, the maximum size is always in character length semantics.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Character length semantics is the default and only length semantics for `NCHAR` or `NVARCHAR2`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The Oracle Database numeric data types store fixed and floating-point numbers, zero, and infinity.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Some numeric types also store values that are the undefined result of an operation, which is known as "not a number" or `NaN`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database stores numeric data in variable-length format.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Each value is stored in scientific notation, with 1 byte used to store the exponent.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The database uses up to 20 bytes to store the mantissa, which is the part of a floating-point number that contains its significant digits.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database does not store leading and trailing zeros.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The `NUMBER` data type stores fixed and floating-point numbers.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The database can store numbers of virtually any magnitude.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] This data is guaranteed to be portable among different operating systems running Oracle Database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The `NUMBER` data type is recommended for most cases in which you must store numeric data.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In Example 2-1, the `salary` column is type `NUMBER(8,2)`, so the precision is 8 and the scale is 2.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database provides two numeric data types exclusively for floating-point numbers: `BINARY_FLOAT` and `BINARY_DOUBLE`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] These types support all of the basic functionality provided by the `NUMBER` data type.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] However, whereas `NUMBER` uses decimal precision, `BINARY_FLOAT` and `BINARY_DOUBLE` use binary precision, which enables faster arithmetic calculations and usually reduces storage requirements.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] `BINARY_FLOAT` and `BINARY_DOUBLE` are approximate numeric data types.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] They store approximate representations of decimal values, rather than exact representations.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, the value 0.1 cannot be exactly represented by either `BINARY_DOUBLE` or `BINARY_FLOAT`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] They are frequently used for scientific computations.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Their behavior is similar to the data types `FLOAT` and `DOUBLE` in Java and XMLSchema.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The datetime data types are `DATE` and `TIMESTAMP`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database provides comprehensive time zone support for time stamps.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The `DATE` data type stores date and time.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Although datetimes can be represented in character or number data types, `DATE` has special associated properties.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The database stores dates internally as numbers.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Dates are stored in fixed-length fields of 7 bytes each, corresponding to century, year, month, day, hour, minute, and second.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Dates fully support arithmetic operations, so you add to and subtract from dates just as you can with numbers.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The database displays dates according to the specified format model.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A format model is a character literal that describes the format of a datetime in a character string.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The standard date format is `DD-MON-RR`, which displays dates in the form `01-JAN-11`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] `RR` is similar to `YY` (the last two digits of the year), but the century of the return value varies according to the specified two-digit year and the last two digits of the current year.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Assume that in 1999 the database displays `01-JAN-11`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] If the date format uses `RR`, then `11` specifies `2011`, whereas if the format uses `YY`, then `11` specifies `1911`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] You can change the default date format at both the database instance and session level.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database stores time in 24-hour format—`HH:MI:SS`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] If no time portion is entered, then by default the time in a date field is `00:00:00 A.M`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In a time-only entry, the date portion defaults to the first day of the current month.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The `TIMESTAMP` data type is an extension of the `DATE` data type.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] `TIMESTAMP` stores fractional seconds in addition to the information stored in the `DATE` data type.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The `TIMESTAMP` data type is useful for storing precise time values, such as in applications that must track event order.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The `DATETIME` data types `TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE` and `TIMESTAMP WITH LOCAL TIME ZONE` are time-zone aware.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] When a user selects the data, the value is adjusted to the time zone of the user session.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] This data type is useful for collecting and evaluating date information across geographic regions.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Every row stored in the database has an address– an internal representation to locate that row within the database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database uses a `ROWID` data type to store the address (rowid) of every row in the database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A data type called the universal rowid, or urowid, supports all types of rowids.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database uses rowids internally for the construction of indexes.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A B-tree index, which is the most common type, contains an ordered list of keys divided into ranges.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Each key is associated with a rowid that points to the associated row's address for fast access.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] While you can create tables with columns defined using the `ROWID` data type, you should not store rowids with the intention of using them to access data at a later stage.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Using rowids in this manner may yield unpredictable or incorrect results.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The `rowid` for a row may change for a number of reasons which may be user initiated or internally by the database engine.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] You cannot depend on the `rowid` to be pointing to the same row or a valid row at all after any of these operations has occurred.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Every table in an Oracle database has a pseudocolumn named `ROWID`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A pseudocolumn behaves like a table column, but is not actually stored in the table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] You can select from pseudocolumns, but you cannot insert, update, or delete their values.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A pseudocolumn is also similar to a SQL function without arguments.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Functions without arguments typically return the same value for every row in the result set, whereas pseudocolumns typically return a different value for each row.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Values of the `ROWID` pseudocolumn are strings representing the address of each row.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] These strings have the data type `ROWID`.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] This pseudocolumn is not evident when listing the structure of a table by executing `SELECT` or `DESCRIBE`, nor does the pseudocolumn consume space.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] However, the rowid of each row can be retrieved with a SQL query using the reserved word `ROWID` as a column name.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A format model is a character literal that describes the format of datetime or numeric data stored in a character string.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] A format model does not change the internal representation of the value in the database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] When you convert a character string into a date or number, a format model determines how the database interprets the string.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In SQL, you can use a format model as an argument of the `TO_CHAR` and `TO_DATE` functions to format a value to be returned from the database or to format a value to be stored in the database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] An **integrity constraint** is a named rule that restrict the values for one or more columns in a table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Data integrity rules prevent invalid data entry into tables.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Also, constraints can prevent the deletion of a table when certain dependencies exist.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] If a constraint is enabled, then the database checks data as it is entered or updated.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] Oracle Database prevents data that does not conform to the constraint from being entered.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] If a constraint is disabled, then Oracle Database allows data that does not conform to the constraint to enter the database.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] In Example 2-1, the `CREATE TABLE` statement specifies `NOT NULL` constraints for the `last_name`, `email`, `hire_date`, and `job_id` columns.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] The constraint clauses identify the columns and the conditions of the constraint.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] These constraints ensure that the specified columns contain no null values.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] For example, an attempt to insert a new employee without a job ID generates an error.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] You can create a constraint when or after you create a table.
[src:oracle-database/tables-and-table-clusters-p02] You can temporarily disable constraints if needed.
